utoDW-112\"/><br />[[Hechi]]\n|District\n|Guangxi\n|2020-02-05\n|\n|330,131\n|2010\n|One person per household every day\n|-\n|[[Jiangxi]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-113\"/>\n|Province\n| \u2013\n|2020-02-06\n|\n|45,200,000\n|2013\n|\n|-\n|[[Xianyang]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-114\"/>\n|City\n|Shaanxi\n|2020-02-06\n|\n|5,096,001\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Jinzhou]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-115\"/>\n|City\n|Liaoning\n|2020-02-06\n|\n|3,070,000\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Kuancheng District|Kuancheng]],<ref name=\"AutoDW-116\"/><br />[[Changchun]]\n|District\n|Jilin\n|2020-02-06\n|\n|680,631\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Tangshan]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-117\"/>\n|City\n|Hebei\n|2020-02-07\n|\n|7,935,800\n|2018\n|\n|-\n|[[Baodi District|Baodi]], Tianjin\n|District\n|Tianjin\n|2020-02-09\n|\n|799,057\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Hubei]]\n|Province\n| \u2013\n|2020-02-16\n|\n|59,020,000\n|2018\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''All'''\n|\n|\n|233,441,748\n|\n|Sum of census data and population estimates above\n|}\n\n==== Speciality hospitals ====\nA speciality hospital named [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] has been constructed as a countermeasure against the outbreak and to better quarantine the patients. Wuhan City government had demanded that a state-owned enterprise construct such a hospital \"at the fastest speed\" comparable to that of the [[Timeline of the SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak in 2003]].<ref name=\"Outbreak\"/> On 24 January, Wuhan authorities specified its planning, saying they planned to have Huoshenshan Hospital built within six days of the announcement and it will be ready to use on 3 February. Upon opening, the speciality hospital has 1,000 beds<ref name=\"20200128www\"/> and takes up 30,000 square metres. The hospital is modelled after the {{ill|Xiaotangshan Hospital|2=zh|3=\u5c0f\u6c64\u5c71\u533b\u9662|preserve=1}}, which was fabricated for the SARS outbreak of 2003, itself built in only seven days.<ref name=\"Xinhua Huoshenshan\"/><ref name=\"20200124theguardian-plans\"/> State media reported that there were 7,000 workers and nearly 300 units of construction machinery on the site at peak.<ref name=\"chinanews9069083\"/>\n\nOn 24 January 2020, the authority announced that they would convert an empty building in [[Huangzhou District]], Huanggang to a 1,000-bed hospital named [[Dabie Mountain Regional Medical Centre]]. Works began the next day by 500 personnel and the building began accepting patients on 28 January 2020 at 10:30&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"metro12142899\"/> In Wuhan, authorities have seized dormitories, offices and hospitals to create more beds for patients.<ref name=\"AutoDW-185\"/> On 25 January authorities announced plans for [[Leishenshan Hospital]], a second speciality hospital, with a capacity of 1,600 beds;<ref name=\"bjnews681160\"/> operations are scheduled to start by 6 February.<ref name=\"yicai20200131\"/><ref name=\"people33744294\"/> Some people voiced their concerns through social media services, saying the authorities' decision to build yet another hospital in such little time showed the severity of the outbreak could be a lot worse than expected.<ref name=\"AutoDW-184\"/> The hospital opened on 8 February.<ref name=\"CGTN09\">{{cite news|date=9 February 2020|url=https://america.cgtn.com/2020/02/09/first-30-viral-pneumonia-patients-admitted-in-leishenshan-hospital|title=First 30 viral pneumonia patients admitted in Leishenshan Hospital|publisher=CGTN|accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n14 temporary hospitals were constructed in China in total, but all were reported to have closed after the crisis was determined be under control on 10 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51813876 |title=Coronavirus: China says disease 'curbed' in Wuhan and Hubei | date=10 March 2020 |work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"250px\" heights=\"200px\" >\nFile:Wuhan Huoshenshan Hospital under construction 02.jpg|Construction site of [[Huoshenshan Hospital]] as it appeared on 24 January\n</gallery>\n\n==== Interprovincial medical aid ====\n[https://www.coronavirus786.com/2020/04/Chinese-Vaccine-Approved-for-Human-Testing-at-Virus-Epicenter.html Chinese coronavirus vaccine Approved for Human]\n\nThe [https://www.coronavirus786.com/2020/04/Chinese-Vaccine-Approved-for-Human-Testing-at-Virus-Epicenter.html coronavirus vaccine] will not be earlier than autumn 2020\n[https://www.coronavirus786.com/2020/04/Chinese-Vaccine-Approved-for-Human-Testing-at-Virus-Epicenter.html Coronavirus vaccine] trials are starting in China, the USA, and Canada with a few days difference. Of course, no one knows what the results will be. And while doctors and scientists analyze the results, we talk about how the world came to the first vaccine so quickly, and what was done along the way.\n\nAs of 16 February 2020, 217 teams of a total of 25,633 medical workers from across China went to Wuhan and other cities in Hubei to help open up more facilities and treat patients.<ref name=\"AutoDW-118\"/>\n\n==== Censorship and police responses ====\n{{See also|Censorship in China|Internet censorship in China|Human rights issues during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus_pandemic#Censorship}}\n[[File:\u674e\u6587\u4eae\u7684\u8bad\u8beb\u4e66.png|right|thumb|Document issued by the Wuhan Police ordering [[Li Wenliang]] to stop \"spreading rumours\" about a possible 'SARS virus' dated 3 January.]]\nThe early response by city authorities was criticised as prioritising a control of information that might be unfavorable for local officials over public safety, and China was also criticised for cover-ups and\ndownplaying the initial discovery and severity of the outbreak. By the time China had informed the WHO of the new coronavirus on 31 December 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the government was still keeping \"its own citizens in the dark\".<ref name=\"TrueCost\">{{Cite web|url= https://nationalpost.com/news/the-true-cost-of-chinas-coronavirus-cover-up-how-state-censorship-let-the-outbreak-spread |title=The true cost of China's coronavirus cover-up: How state censorship let the outbreak spread |publisher=Financial Times |via=Nationalpost.com |date=7 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"FaceXi\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/23/asia/wuhan-china-coronavirus-sars-response-intl-hnk/index.html |title=Wuhan is the latest crisis to face China's Xi, and it's exposing major flaws in his model of control |last=Griffiths |first=James |publisher=CNN |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208194710/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/23/asia/wuhan-china-coronavirus-sars-response-intl-hnk/index.html |archive-date=8 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Observers have attributed this to the censorship institutional structure of the country's press and Internet, exacerbated by China's [[paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]]'s crackdown on independent oversight such as journalism and social media that left senior officials with inaccurate information on the outbreak and \"contributed to a prolonged period of inaction that allowed the virus to spread\".<ref name=\"TrueCost\" /><ref name=\"FaceXi\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/29/opinion/coronavirus-china-government.html|access-date=2 March 2020|\ntitle=Coronavirus Spreads, and the World Pays for China's Dictatorship|date=29 January 2020|first1=Nicholas|last1=Kristof|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/world/asia/2020/01/china-s-slow-response-coronavirus-has-shown-weakness-its-centralised-model |title=China's slow response to coronavirus has shown the weakness of its centralised model |website=New Statesman |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128134506/https://www.newstatesman.com/world/asia/2020/01/china-s-slow-response-coronavirus-has-shown-weakness-its-centralised-model |archive-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>  The [[Human Rights Watch]] also noted censorship by the authorities of social media posts from families of infected people who were potentially seeking help as well as by people living in cordoned cities who were documenting their daily lives amidst the lockdown.<ref name=\"20200130hrw\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/01/30/china-respect-rights-coronavirus-response |title=China: Respect Rights in Coronavirus Response |date=30 January 2020 |publisher=Human Rights Watch |access-date=31 January 2020 |last3=t 1.212.290.4700 |first3=NY 10118-3299 USA {{!}} |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203095738/https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/01/30/china-respect-rights-coronavirus-response |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA group of eight medical personnel, including [[Li Wenliang]], an ophthalmologist from Wuhan Central Hospital who in late December posted warnings on a new coronavirus strain akin to SARS, were taken into custody by Wuhan police and threatened with prosecution for \"spreading rumours\" for likening it to SARS.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.worldjournal.com/6771702/article-\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u7b2c\u4e00\u500b\u5439\u54e8\u8005-\u674e\u6587\u4eae\u91ab\u5e2b\u904e\u4e16/ |title=\u65b0\u51a0\u80ba\u708e\u5439\u54e8\u91ab\u5e2b \u674e\u6587\u4eae\u75c5\u901d \u6c11\u773e\u6fc0\u61a4|date=7 February 2020|website=\u4e16\u754c\u65b0\u805e\u7db2|language=zh-TW|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51403795|title=Coronavirus kills Chinese whistleblower doctor|date=7 February 2020|publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>  Li Wenliang later died of the disease on 7 February, and was widely hailed as a whistleblower in China, but some of the trending hashtags on [[Sina Weibo|Weibo]] such as \"Wuhan government owes Dr Li Wenliang an apology\" and \"We want freedom of speech\" were blocked.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/technology/china-coronavirus-censorship-social-media.html |title=As Virus Spreads, Anger Floods Chinese Social Media |last=Zhong |first=Raymond |date=27 January 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128115157/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/27/technology/china-coronavirus-censorship-social-media.html |archive-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51409801|title=Li Wenliang: Coronavirus death of Wuhan doctor sparks outpouring of anger|date=7 February 2020|publisher=[[BBC News]]|access-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207062254/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-51409801|archive-date=7 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Graham-Harrison|first=Emma|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/07/coronavirus-chinese-rage-death-whistleblower-doctor-li-wenliang|title='Hero who told the truth': Chinese rage over coronavirus death of whistleblower doctor|date=6 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 February 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200207062759/https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/07/coronavirus-chinese-rage-death-whistleblower-doctor-li-wenliang|archive-date=7 February 2020}}</ref> His death widespread public anger in the aftermath, in what has been described as \"one of the biggest outpourings of online criticism of the government in years,\" was not a topic that was permitted for coverage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/07/li-wenliangs-death-is-a-new-crisis-for-chinas-rulers|title=Li Wenliang's death is a new crisis for China's rulers|work=The Economist|access-date=12 February 2020|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> One media outlet sent notices to editors, and leaked to reporters, asking them to refrain from \"commenting or speculating\" and giving instructions to \"not hashtag and let the topic gradually die out from the hot search list, and guard against harmful information.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-health-censorship/chinas-online-censors-tighten-grip-after-brief-coronavirus-respite-idUKKBN2051BV |title=China's online censors tighten grip after brief coronavirus respite |date=11 February 2020|work=Reuters }}</ref><ref name=\"TruthSeekers\">{{cite web|url= https://nationalpost.com/opinion/terry-glavin-china-is-disappearing-coronavirus-truth-seekers |title=Terry Glavin: China is 'disappearing' coronavirus truth-seekers |work=National Post|last=Glavin |first=Terry |date=12 February 2020 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January, [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] made his first public remark on the outbreak and spoke of \"the need for the timely release of information\".<ref name=\"xinhuanet138721535\">{{Cite news |url=http://xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/20/c_138721535.htm |title=Xi orders resolute efforts to curb virus spread |date=20 January 2020 |access-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124174142/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/20/c_138721535.htm |archive-date=24 January 2020 |agency=Xinhua News Agency}}</ref> One day later, the CPC [[Central Political and Legal Affairs Commission]], the most powerful political organ in China overseeing legal enforcement and the police, wrote \"self-deception will only make the epidemic worse and turn a natural disaster that was controllable into a man-made disaster at great cost,\" and \"only openness can minimise panic to the greatest extent.\" The commission then added, \"anyone who deliberately delays and hides the reporting of cases out of self-interest will be nailed on a pillar of shame for eternity.\"<ref name=\"20200122washingtonpost\">{{Cite news |last=Fifield |first=Anna |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinese-officials-urge-people-not-to-travel-in-and-out-of-city-at-center-of-virus-outbreak/2020/01/21/60680d3e-3c2d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html |title=Chinese officials try to contain virus outbreak as first case confirmed in U.S. |date=22 January 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124175758/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/chinese-officials-urge-people-not-to-travel-in-and-out-of-city-at-center-of-virus-outbreak/2020/01/21/60680d3e-3c2d-11ea-afe2-090eb37b60b1_story.html |archive-date=24 January 2020 |last2=Sun |first2=Lina H. |last3=Bernstein |first3=Lenny}}</ref><ref name=\"scmp3046984\">{{Cite news |last=Zheng |first=William |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3046984/china-warns-cadres-cover-spread-virus-and-be-nailed-pillar |title=China's credibility on the line as it tries to dispels fears it will cover up spread of Wuhan virus |date=21 January 2020 |work=South China Morning Post |access-date=25 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125014942/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/politics/article/3046984/china-warns-cadres-cover-spread-virus-and-be-nailed-pillar |archive-date=25 January 2020 |last2=Lau |first2=Mimi}}</ref> Xi Jinping later also instructed authorities \"to strengthen the guidance of public opinions\", language which some view as a call for censorship after commentators on social media became increasingly pointedly critical and angry at the government due to the epidemic.<ref name=\"WSJ\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-strains-to-stamp-out-coronavirus-criticisms-at-home-11580207403 |title=China Strains to Stamp Out Coronavirus Criticisms at Home |last=Wei |first=Lingling |date=28 January 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=29 January 2020 |issn=0099-9660 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>  on 30 January, [[Supreme People's Court|China's Supreme Court]], delivered a rare rebuke against the country's police forces, calling the \"unreasonably harsh crackdown on online rumours\" as undermining public trust. The supreme court judge Tang Xinghua said that if police had been lenient against rumours and allowed the public to have taken heed of them, an earlier adoption of \"measures like wearing masks, strictly disinfecting and avoiding wildlife markets\" might have been useful in countering the spread of the epidemic.<ref name=\"20200130Guardian\">{{Cite news  |first1=Alison |last1=Rourke|first2= Molly |last2=Blackall |first3= Damien |last3=Gayle |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/jan/30/coronavirus-live-updates-china-death-toll-wuhan-evacuation-foreign-nationals-citizens-latest-news |title=Virus death toll reaches 213 in China \u2013 as it happened |date=31 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=2 February 2020 |last4=Weaver |first4=Matthew |issn=0261-3077 |first5= Jessica|last5=Murray |last6=Doherty |first6=Ben |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130002626/https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/jan/30/coronavirus-live-updates-china-death-toll-wuhan-evacuation-foreign-nationals-citizens-latest-news |archive-date=30 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the central government's \"bifurcated approach to diffuse discontent\", citizens were permitted to criticise local officials so long as they did not \"question the basic legitimacy of the party\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-coronavirus-outbreak-chinas-leaders-scramble-to-avert-a-chernobyl-moment/2020/01/29/bc4eb52a-4250-11ea-99c7-1dfd4241a2fe_story.html |title=In coronavirus pandemic, China's leaders scramble to avert a Chernobyl moment |website=The Washington Post |access-date=10 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204085411/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-coronavirus-outbreak-chinas-leaders-scramble-to-avert-a-chernobyl-moment/2020/01/29/bc4eb52a-4250-11ea-99c7-1dfd4241a2fe_story.html |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Cyberspace Administration of China|Cyberspace Administration]] (CAC) declared its intent to foster a \"good online atmosphere,\" with CAC notices sent to video platforms encouraging them to \"not to push any negative story, and not to conduct non-official livestreaming on the virus.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-censorship-idUSKBN2051BP|title=China's online censors tighten grip after brief coronavirus respite|date=11 February 2020|agency=Reuters|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Censorship has been observed being applied on news articles and social media posts deemed to hold negative tones about the coronavirus and the governmental response, including posts mocking Xi Jinping for not visiting areas of the epidemic,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/04/blame-xi-jinping-absence-coronavirus-frontline-china-crisis|title=Taking credit, avoiding blame? Xi Jinping's absence from coronavirus frontline|last=Kuo|first=Lily|date=4 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 February 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204231032/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/04/blame-xi-jinping-absence-coronavirus-frontline-china-crisis|archive-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> an article that predicted negative effects of the epidemic on the economy, and calls to remove local government officials.<ref name=\"auto5\" /><ref name=\"auto3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/asia/wuhan-virus-china-censorship-intl-hnk/index.html|title=China is waking up to the dangers of knee-jerk censorship in a crisis|first=James|last=Griffiths|publisher=CNN|access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202033436/https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/31/asia/wuhan-virus-china-censorship-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=2 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/g5xykx/you-can-now-go-to-jail-in-china-for-criticizing-beijings-coronavirus-response|title=You Can Now Go to Jail in China for Criticizing Beijing's Coronavirus Response|last=Gilbert|first=David|date=30 January 2020|website=Vice|access-date=2 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131082945/https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/g5xykx/you-can-now-go-to-jail-in-china-for-criticizing-beijings-coronavirus-response|archive-date=31 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  While censorship had been briefly relaxed giving a \"window of about two weeks in which Chinese journalists were able to publish hard-hitting stories exposing the mishandling of the novel coronavirus by officials\", since then private news outlets were reportedly required to use \"planned and controlled publicity\" with the authorities' consent.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-censorship/chinas-online-censors-tighten-grip-after-brief-coronavirus-respite-idUSKBN2051BP|title=China's online censors tighten grip after brief coronavirus respite|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=22 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n==== Approval of Chinese responses ====\n[[File:President Trump Addresses a Briefing on the Coronavirus (49463760243).jpg|thumb|On 29 January, President Trump received a briefing on the coronavirus in China.]]\n\nChina's response to the virus, in comparison to the [[2003 SARS outbreak]], has been praised by some foreign leaders.<ref>{{Cite news |last=AFP |url= https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-virus-120012500107_1.html |title=Trump praises China 'efforts and transparency' on virus |date=25 January 2020 |work=Business Standard India |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200125151634/https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-virus-120012500107_1.html |archive-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> U.S. President Trump thanked Chinese leader Xi Jinping \"on behalf of the American People\" on 24 January on Twitter, stating that \"China has been working very hard to contain the Coronavirus. The United States greatly appreciates their efforts and transparency\" and declaring that \"It will all work out well.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-wuhan-virus |title=Trump praises China 'efforts and transparency' on Wuhan virus |date=25 January 2020 |work=[[The Straits Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200127163253/https://www.straitstimes.com/world/united-states/trump-praises-china-efforts-and-transparency-on-wuhan-virus |archive-date=27 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Germany's health minister [[Jens Spahn]], in an interview on ''[[Bloomberg Television|Bloomberg TV]]'', said with comparison to the Chinese response to SARS in 2003: \"There's a big difference to SARS. We have a much more transparent China. The action of China is much more effective in the first days already.\" He also praised the international co-operation and communication in dealing with the virus.<<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-reaches-europe-as-france-confirms-3-cases/a-52145333 |title=Coronavirus reaches Europe as France confirms 3 cases |date=24 January 2020 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-01-24/china-doing-good-job-in-combating-virus-german-minister-says |title=China Doing Good Job in Combating Virus, German Minister Says |work=[[Bloomberg News]] |access-date=28 January 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In a letter to Xi, Singaporean president [[Halimah Yacob]] applauded China's \"swift, decisive and comprehensive measures\" in safeguarding the health of the Chinese people, while prime minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] remarked of \"China's firm and decisive response\" in communities affected by the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/covid19-coronavirus-singapore-china-solidarity-12465678 |title=Singapore leaders stand in solidarity with China over COVID-19 outbreak |work=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> Similar sentiments were expressed by Russian president [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3050782/russia-and-china-pledge-maintain-special-relationship-despite |title=Russia and China pledge to maintain special relationship despite Moscow's slow response to coronavirus |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |access-date=24 February 2020 |date=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt a Sunday mass at [[St. Peter's Square]] in Vatican City on 26 January, [[Pope Francis]] praised \"the great commitment by the Chinese community that has already been put in place to combat the epidemic\" and commenced a closing prayer for \"the people who are sick because of the virus that has spread through China\".<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-pope-idUSKBN1ZP0EP |title=Pope Francis praises China's efforts to contain coronavirus |date=26 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020 |work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n== In other countries ==\n{{2020 coronavirus quarantines outside Hubei}}\n\n===In Asia===\n==== South Korea ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea}}\nThe first confirmed case of the coronavirus was identified with a 35-year-old Chinese woman on 20 January. The first South Korean national to be infected occurred three days later was a 55-year-old man who worked in Wuhan and returned for a checkup with flu symptoms. The two infection reports were publicly released on 24 January. The sixth patient was the first case in South Korea who had never visited Wuhan. The 56-year-old man caught the virus when visiting a restaurant with the third patient.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Coronavirus Jongno 1.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus infection prevention tips banner in Seoul, South Korea]]\nA woman, who had returned from [[Thailand]] after a five-day vacation, was tested positive and confirmed as the sixteenth case on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus|title=Coronavirus: South Korean woman travelling home from Thailand tests positive for virus|date=4 February 2020|website=The Straits Times|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204092646/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus|archive-date=4 February 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> Three more cases were confirmed on 5 February, bringing the total case count to 19. The seventeenth and nineteenth patients had attended a conference in Singapore and been in contact with an infected person there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yna.kr/AEN20200205002356320|title=3 More Virus Cases Bring S. Korea's Total to 19, Two Confirmed after Trip to Singapore|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap|url-status=live|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The very same day the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea]] (KCDC) announced that the second patient had been released from hospital after being tested negative in consecutive tests, becoming the country's first coronavirus patient to fully recover.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|title=S. Korea Releases First Fully Recovered Coronavirus Patient from Hospital|date=5 February 2020|agency=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205133506/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|archive-date=5 February 2020|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February, the number of confirmed cases increased by 20. On 20 February 70 new cases were confirmed,<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\">{{cite news|last1=Shin|first1=Hyonhee|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea-cases/like-a-zombie-apocalypse-residents-on-edge-as-coronavirus-cases-surge-in-south-korea-idUSKBN20E04F|title='Like a zombie apocalypse': Residents on edge as coronavirus cases surge in South Korea|date=20 February 2020|accessdate=20 February 2020|url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped -->|archiveurl=https://archive.today/D1K5i|archivedate=20 February 2020|agency=[[Thomson Reuters]]|last2=Cha|first2=Sangmi|trans-title=<!-- trans-title is the English translation -->|url-access=<!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> giving a total of 104 confirmed cases, according to the KCDC. According to ''[[Reuters]]'', KCDC attributed the sudden jump to 70 cases linked to \"Patient No. 31\", who had participated in a gathering in [[Daegu]] at the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony]].<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" />\n\nOn 20 February, the streets of Daegu were empty in reaction to the Shincheonji outbreak. A resident described the reaction, stating \"It's like someone dropped a bomb in the middle of the city. It looks like a zombie apocalypse.\"<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> The first death was reported<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|title=South Korea reports first coronavirus death as infections linked to church rise|publisher=NBC News|access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref> in a mental ward of Cheongdo Daenam Hospital in [[Cheongdo County]]. According to the mayor of Daegu, the number of suspected cases as of 21 February was 544 among 4,400 examined followers of the church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html|title=\uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0 \uad00\ub828 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 76\uba85\uc73c\ub85c \ub298\uc5b4...\ub300\uad6c \uad50\uc778 \uc758\uc2ec\uc790\ub9cc 544\uba85|language=ko|trans-title=The number of Shincheonji related doctors will increase to 74 ... Daegu members only 544|date=21 February 2020|publisher=Chosun.com}}</ref> The hospital was suspected as the source of the present outbreak after it was visited by a woman who became the second fatal case of Korea on that day. The infection spread outside via a funeral ceremony attended by members of the church.<ref name=\"b82186\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|title=South Korea virus 'emergency' as cases increase|date=21 February 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"koreabiomed\">{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Han-soo|url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489|title=COVID-19 patients soar to 204 in Korea|date=21 February 2020|work=Korea Biomedical Review|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll South Korean military bases were on lockdown after tests confirmed that three soldiers were indeed positive for the virus.<ref name=\"b82186\" /> Airlines cut connections and cultural schedules were being cancelled due to fears of further spread.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249|title=Airlines to suspend more flights over coronavirus|date=21 February 2020|work=The Korea Herald|accessdate=21 February 2020|agency=Yonhap}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Song|first1=Seung-hyun|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554|title=Foreign artists delay concerts in Korea due to spread of COVID-19|date=21 February 2020|work=The Korea Herald|accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> [[United States Forces Korea]] raised the alert level from low to moderate and cut off non-essential travel to and from USFK Daegu.<ref name=\"MT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|title=US Forces Korea imposes new coronavirus protections after uptick in S Korea cases|date=19 February 2020}}</ref> USFK Daegu's school facilities were closed and non-essential personnel were ordered to stay at home while any visitors going there were not allowed to enter.<ref name=\"MT\" /> USFK announced that the widow of a retired soldier who was in Daegu was diagnosed to be positive for the virus on 24 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023|title=USFK dependent tests positive for coronavirus, putting military on high alert in South Korea|website=Stars and Stripes}}</ref> [[Camp Humphreys]] enacted virus detection protocols, including temperature checks and raised the alert level to high.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2|title=US troops in Korea are on high alert for coronavirus after widow of retired soldier tests positive|first=David|last=Roza|website=Business Insider}}</ref> On 26 February, an American soldier based at Camp Carroll was diagnosed to be positive and was quarantined away from bases via off-base housing unit<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045|title=U.S. Soldier infected as South Korea coronavirus cases rise above 1,260|date=26 February 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref> with contact tracing done that showed his movements to Camp Walker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25|title=First U.S. soldier in South Korea tests positive for coronavirus; towns sealed off in northern Italy|first=Associated|last=Press|website=MarketWatch}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Incheon 2.jpg|thumb|The near-empty arrival hall of [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon International Airport]] in South Korea on 6&nbsp;March]]\n\nAs of 22 February, among 9,336 followers of the church, 1,261 reported symptoms.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec |title=\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669 (2\uc6d4 22\uc77c 09\uc2dc) |date=22 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time, 169 confirmed cases involved the church and another 111 came from the Cheongdo Daenam Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cdc.go.kr/|title=\uc9c8\ubcd1\uad00\ub9ac\ubcf8\ubd80|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea}}</ref> 23 February saw another 123 cases with 75 being from Shincheonji<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1|title=123 additional cases have been confirmed|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=23 February 2020|website=[[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> and 24 February saw 161 additional cases with 129 being from the religious group. Over 27,000 people have been tested for the virus with 19,127 negative results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1|title=161 additional cases have been confirmed|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=24 February 2020|website=[[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 15 countries imposed travel restrictions to and from South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|title=15 countries have travel restrictions on South Korea|date=24 February 2020|publisher=CNN|url-status=live|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that a senior health official overseeing the COVID-19 efforts in Daegu tested positive and was also a member of Shincheonji.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south|title=Coronavirus: infected health official leading South Korea's fight against Covid-19 is member of Shincheonji Church of Jesus doomsday cult|last=Park|first=Chan-kyong|date=24 February 2020|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=25 February 2020|quote=Official in charge of fight against the virus in western Daegu admits being member of cult after testing positive; 50 coworkers quarantined}}</ref><ref name=\":750tested\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance|title=Were you on this bus with a coronavirus patient? South Korea is on the hunt for infections|last=Kim|first=Victoria|date=27 February 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=28 February 2020|quote=Even a public health official in charge of infection prevention in Seo-gu in Daegu was revealed to be a member of the church after he was diagnosed with the virus. Many members hide their affiliation with the controversial church. More than 750,000 signed a petition to the South Korean president urging that the church be disbanded. Authorities in Gyeonggi province raided the group\u2019s headquarters in the city of Gwacheon, alleging that the church had been slow to turn over its list of members. South Korean officials said they would track down and test all 245,000 members of the church.}}</ref> Within a few days, a petition to the nation's president urging for the disbandment of the church had over 750,000 signatures. Their headquarters in [[Gwacheon]] was raided by law enforcement; government officials said all 245,000 members of the religious group would be found and tested.<ref name=\":750tested\" /> On 28 February, over 2,000 confirmed cases were reported,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030|title=The Updates of COVID-19 in Republic of Korea As of 28 February, 2020|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> rising to 3,150 on 29 February.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seekingalpha.com/news/3547240-south-korea-reports-record-jump-in-coronavirus-cases|title=South Korea reports a record jump in coronavirus cases|last=Hoffmann|first=SA Eli|date=29 February 2020|website=Seeking Alpha|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====North Korea====\n[https://www.coronavirus786.com/2020/03/north-korea-corona-virus-victim-shot.html '''North Korea: Coronavirus victim shot dead''']\nNorth Korea officially denies any infection within its borders, but news reports estimate at least 180-200 deaths among the army alone, not counting those among the civilian population. There is no estimate of those merely infected. Army commanders are punished for any deaths in the ranks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3074377/coronavirus-nearly-200-north-korea-soldiers-die-outbreak|title=Coronavirus: nearly 200 North Korea soldiers 'die from outbreak government refuses to acknowledge'|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== India ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|2020 India coronavirus lockdown}}\nThe Indian government airlifted 324 of its citizens from China on 31 January and 1 February via Air India special chartered flights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1803713/air-india-pilot-recalls-wuhan-coronavirus-evacuation-mission/|title=Air India pilot recalls the \"deathly quiet\" in Wuhan amidst coronavirus evacuation|last=Sharma|first=Niharika|website=Quartz India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> After Pakistan's refusal to evacuate its students from Wuhan, the Indian government offered to support them with evacuation along with citizens of other neighbouring countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/india-had-offered-to-evacuate-pakistani-students-from-coronavirus-hit-wuhan-jaishankar-tells-rajya-sabha-1644278-2020-02-07|title=India had offered to evacuate Pakistani students from coronavirus-hit Wuhan, Jaishankar tells Rajya Sabha|last=Delhi7 February|first=India Today Web Desk New|last2=7 February|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09|last3=Ist|first3=2020 18:50}}</ref> On 17 February, India announced a special [[C-17 Globemaster]] flight carrying medical supplies to support China in Wuhan and evacuating citizens of India and neighbouring countries. India eventually evacuated 647 people including citizens of Maldives and Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/china-delaying-permission-to-india-to-send-flight-carrying-relief-materials-to-wuhan/articleshow/74252370.cms?from=mdr|title=Chinese wall stopping evacuation of Indian nationals from Wuhan|date=2020-02-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, after a video conference of [[SAARC]] leaders, PM [[Narendra Modi]] allocated [[Indian rupee|\u20b9]]74 [[crore]] (US$10 million) of funds classified as COVID-19 Emergency Fund for the SAARC countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/saarc-video-conference-live-we-evacuated-1-400-indians-from-different-countries-says-modi-11584273185030.html|title=PM Modi proposes Covid-19 emergency fund to SAARC leaders, offers $10 mn|date=2020-03-15|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a precautionary measure, India had closed all of its international land borders as of March 16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf|title=NewinstructionsDt14032020Restirctiononinternationalpassengertraffic.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mohfw.gov.in/GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf|title=GuidelinesDT13032020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the [[Government of India]] decided to completely lockdown 82 districts in 22 states and Union Territories of country where confirmed cases have been reported till 31 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/82-districts-under-lockdown-over-covid-19-what-s-open-and-what-is-shut/story-c1AEMZXuuXN6FvmrAdRvsJ.html|title=82 districts under lockdown over Covid-19: What is shut and where|last=|first=|date=2020-03-23|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Essential services and commodities were to continue.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jagannath|first1=J.|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-lockdown-to-start-at-6-am-monday-until-31-march-kejriwal-11584881955813.html|title=Delhi lockdown to start at 6 am Monday, until 31 March: Kejriwal|date=22 March 2020|work=Livemint|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/lockdown-in-west-bengal-from-5pm-today-government-to-shut-down-non-essentials/articleshow/74766599.cms|title=Lockdown in West Bengal: From 5pm today, government to shut down non-essentials|date=23 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> 80 cities including major cities such as Bengaluru, Chennai, Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, Nagpur, Varanasi and Raipur were also put under lockdown.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gunasekar|first1=Arvind|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-19-80-cities-across-india-go-into-lockdown-till-march-31-what-it-means-2198894|title=Coronavirus: 80 Cities Across India Go Into Lockdown Till March 31. What It Means|date=23 March 2020|work=NDTV|accessdate=23 March 2020|last2=Bhattacharji|first2=Chetan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Marpakwar|first1=Prafulla|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/poor-public-response-pushed-govt-to-declare-lockdown-in-mumbai/articleshow/74766049.cms|title=Poor public response pushed govt to declare lockdown in Mumbai|date=23 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> On 24 March, the government announced a nationwide lockdown for 21 days, starting from 25 March, till 14 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52024239|title=India's 1.3bn population told to stay at home|date=2020-03-25|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==== Iran ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran}}\n[[File:Disinfection of Tehran subway wagons against coronavirus 2020-02-26 09.jpg|thumb|Disinfection of [[Tehran Metro|Tehran subway]] wagons against coronavirus]]\nIran reported its first confirmed cases of SARS-CoV-2 infections on 19 February 2020 in [[Qom]], where according to the [[Ministry of Health and Medical Education]], both had died later that day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Arrives in Iran: Two People Test Positive in Qom |url=http://irangov.ir/detail/334964 |website=irangov.ir |date= 19 February 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Iran Confirms 3 New Coronavirus Cases |url=http://irangov.ir/detail/335028 |website=irangov.ir |date= 20 February 2020 |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly measures announced by the government included the cancellation of concerts and other cultural events,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iranian-doctors-call-for-long-holiday-to-contain-coronavirus-outbreak/30449047.html |title=Iranian Doctors Call For 'Long Holiday' To Contain Coronavirus, As Sixth Victim Dies |website=Radio Farda |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=22 February 2020 |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> sporting events,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.varzesh3.com/news/1669982/\u0644\u063a\u0648-\u0647\u0645\u0647-\u0645\u0633\u0627\u0628\u0642\u0627\u062a-\u0648\u0631\u0632\u0634\u06cc-\u0628\u0647-\u0645\u062f\u062a-\u0631\u0648\u0632|title=\u0644\u063a\u0648 \u0647\u0645\u0647 \u0645\u0633\u0627\u0628\u0642\u0627\u062a \u0648\u0631\u0632\u0634\u06cc \u0628\u0647 \u0645\u062f\u062a \u06f1\u06f0 \u0631\u0648\u0632|website=varzesh3.com|language=Persian|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> and Friday prayers,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gambrell|first=Jon|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/saudi-arabia-halts-travel-to-islams-holiest-site-over-virus%2f2020%2f02%2f26%2fc86ec712-5918-11ea-8efd-0f904bdd8057_story.html|title=Iran news agencies report Friday prayers canceled in Tehran|agency=Associated Press|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> closure of universities, higher education institutions and schools,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/iran-announces-closure-of-universities-schools-to-fight-coronavirus/30449711.html|title=Iran Announces Closure Of Universities, Schools As Coronavirus Death Toll Rises|website=Radio Farda|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=2020-02-23|accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref> and allocated 5&nbsp;trillion rials to combat the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jamaran.news/\u0628\u062e\u0634-\u067e\u0631\u0648\u0641\u0627\u06cc\u0644-182/1363201-\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635-\u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f-\u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646-\u0628\u0647-\u0648\u0632\u0627\u0631\u062a-\u0628\u0647\u062f\u0627\u0634\u062a-\u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc-\u0645\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0647-\u0628\u0627-\u06a9\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627|title=\u0627\u062e\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0635 530 \u0645\u06cc\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0631\u062f \u062a\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0647 \u0648\u0632\u0627\u0631\u062a \u0628\u0647\u062f\u0627\u0634\u062a \u0628\u0631\u0627\u06cc \u0645\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644\u0647 \u0628\u0627 \u06a9\u0631\u0648\u0646\u0627|website=\u067e\u0627\u06cc\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u062e\u0628\u0631\u06cc \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u2013 \u0627\u0645\u0627\u0645 \u062e\u0645\u06cc\u0646\u06cc \u2013 \u0627\u0646\u0642\u0644\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc|language=fa|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>  President [[Hassan Rouhani]]  said on 26 February 2020 that there were no plans to quarantine areas affected by the outbreak, and only individuals would be quarantined.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51651454|title=Coronavirus: Iran has no plans to quarantine cities, Rouhani says|date=26 February 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref> However, [[Shia]] shrines in Qom remained open to pilgrims.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Ramin Mostaghim |author2=Mostafa Salem |author3=Tamara Qiblawi|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/26/middleeast/iran-coronavirus-intl/index.html|title=Iran was already struggling with one crisis. Now it has the worst coronavirus pandemic in the Middle East|date=26 February 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nIran became a center of the spread of the virus after China.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/world/middleeast/coronavirus-iran.html |title='Recipe for a Massive Viral Outbreak': Iran Emerges as a Worldwide Threat |date=24 February 2020|work=The New York Times |authors= David D. Kirkpatrick, Farnaz Fassihi and Mujib Mashal  }}</ref><ref name=newyorker /> Amidst claims of a cover-up of the extent of the outbreak in the country,<ref>{{cite news|authors=Sam Jones, Aamna Mohdin and agencies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/24/coronavirus-dead-in-iranian-city-of-qom|title=Coronavirus: Iran denies cover-up as six deaths reported in Italy|work=The Guardian|date=24 February 2020}}</ref> over ten countries have traced their cases back to Iran, indicating that the extent of the outbreak may be more severe than that admitted by the Iranian government.<ref name=newyorker>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/how-iran-became-a-new-epicenter-of-the-coronavirus-outbreak|title=How Iran Became A New Epicenter of the coronavirus pandemic|last1=Wright|first1=Robin |date=24 February 2020 |work=The New Yorker}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus pummels Iran leadership as data show spread is far worse than reported|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/coronavirus-pummels-iran-leadership-as-data-show-spread-is-far-worse-than-reported/2020/03/04/7b1196ae-5c9f-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=4 March 2020|authors=Erin Cunningham & Dalton Bennett }}</ref> The [[Islamic Consultative Assembly|Iranian Parliament]] was shut down, with 23 of the 290 members of parliament reported to have had tested positive for the virus on 3 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/8-percent-iran-parliament-has-coronavirus-it-released-54000-prisoners-2020-3|title=8% of Iran's parliament has the coronavirus, and it released 54,000 prisoners as the country descends into chaos|last=Haltiwanger|first=John|website=Business Insider|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> A number of senior government officials as well as two members of parliament have died from the disease.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-51801968 |title=Virus hits highest levels of Iran's government |author= Tse Yin Lee |date=9 March 2020 |work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==== Japan ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Japan}}\nOn 27 February 2020, Prime Minister [[Shinzo Abe]] requested that all Japanese elementary, junior high, and high schools close until early April to help contain the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/02/c3c57bbce11d-breaking-news-govt-will-ask-all-schools-in-japan-to-shut-for-virus-fears-abe.html|title=PM Abe asks all schools in Japan to temporarily close over coronavirus|first=KYODO|last=NEWS|website=Kyodo News+}}</ref>\n\nThe outbreak has been a concern for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] which is scheduled to take place in Tokyo starting at the end of July.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Tokyo 2020 could be postponed to end of year \u2013 Japan's Olympic minister |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/olympics/51717839 |publisher=BBC News |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> The Japanese government has thus been taking extra precautions to help minimise the outbreak's impact.<ref name=\"olympicstokyo\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus could see the Tokyo Olympics cancelled. Is Japan's handling of the outbreak to blame? |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-03/coronavirus-will-the-diamond-princess-sink-japans-olympics-dream/12015202 |publisher=ABC News |date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Philippines ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{summarize section|date=March 2020}}\nThe first COVID-19 death outside China occurred in the Philippines on 21 January.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/02/20/ph-records-first-death-due-to-new-coronavirus|title=First novel coronavirus death outside China recorded in PH - WHO official|date=3 February 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of March 14, 2020, the number of confirmed cases in the country was 64.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/|title=COVID-19 Philippine Cases|publisher=Republic of the Philippines - Department of Health|date=14 March 2020|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, 2020, [[Rodrigo Duterte|President Rodrigo R. Duterte]] suspended classes in all levels in Metro Manila from 10 to 15 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253913-new-confirmed-novel-coronavirus-cases-march-9-2020|title=Duterte announces 4 more novel coronavirus cases in PH|date=9 February 2020|work=Rappler|access-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe class suspension in Metro Manila was extended to April 12, 2020, following the decision of concerned authorities to raise the COVID-19 alert level in the country to Code Red Sublevel 2. Work in the executive branch of the government was also suspended for the same period as part of the Stringent Social Distancing Measures in the National Capital Region (NCR),<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://pia.gov.ph/press-releases/releases/1036193|title=Statement of Presidential Spokesperson Salvador Panelo on Code Red Sublevel 2|date=12 March 2020|work=Philippine Information Agency|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with the directive for the concerned government agencies to form skeletal forces to ensure the delivery of basic services. Congress and the Judiciary were encouraged to do the same. Agencies providing law enforcement services, health services, and emergency services were enjoined to continue to operate at full capacity.\n\nOther salient directives, contained in a resolution adopted by the Inter-Agency Task Force on the Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF-EID) and announced by the Philippine President on March 12, 2020 at the Heroes Hall in [[Malaca\u00f1ang Palace|Malaca\u00f1an Palace]],<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036195|title=PRRD orders 'stringent social distancing measures' in NCR|date=12 March 2020|work=Philippine Information Agency|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> include:\n\n# the prohibition of mass gatherings that could strain the resources of the host community,\n# the imposition of community quarantine over [[Metro Manila]], with guidelines issued to Local Government Units outside Metro Manila for the imposition of community quarantine in their respective localities, \n# encouragement of flexible work arrangements for the private sector, subject to guidelines from the [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] and the [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]],\n# the continued operation of mass public transport within Metro Manila (such as [[Manila Light Rail Transit System|LRT]], [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System|MRT]], and [[Philippine National Railways|PNR]]), as well as of manufacturing, retail and service establishments, but with the proviso to enforce strict social distancing, and\n# suspension of land, domestic air, and domestic sea travel to and from Metro Manila from March 15 to April 12, 2020.\n\nOn March 13, 2020, a memorandum containing the guidelines for stringent social distancing measures and the management of COVID-19 in the National Capital Region<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/13/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-stringent-social-distancing-measures-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Stringent Social Distancing Measures and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (Covid-19) Situation|date=13 March 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> was issued by Executive Secretary [[Salvador Medialdea]] by order of the president. Among the directives embodied in the memorandum were:\n* suspension of classes and all school activities until April 14, 2020,\n* prohibition of mass gatherings including \"movie screenings, concerts, sports events and other entertainment activities, community assemblies, and non-essential work-related gatherings.\"\n* imposition of strict social distancing - at least 1 meter radius between and among attendees - during essential meetings and religious activities, and\n* provisions for alternative and/or flexible work arrangements.\n\nOn March 16, the president signed Proclamation No. 929<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/proclamation-no-929-s-2020/|title=Proclamation No. 929 s. 2020 Declaring a State of Calamity Throughout the Philippines due to Corona Virus Disease 2019|date=17 March 2020|publisher=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> declaring a state of calamity throughout the country for a period of six months, bringing into effect the following:\n* price control of basic needs and commodities,\n* granting of interest-free loans,\n* distribution of calamity funds,\n* authorization of importation and receipt of donations, and\n* hazard allowance for public health workers and government personnel in the fields of science and technology.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/laginghanda/dagling-paliwanag-ano-ang-state-of-calamity/|title=Dagling Paliwanag: Ano ang State of Calamity?|publisher=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the sharp increase of confirmed cases, President Duterte called Congress to a special session to \"authorize the President to exercise powers necessary to carry out urgent measures to meet the current national emergency related to the Coronavirus Disease (Covid-19).\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1097429|title=Duterte seeks \u2018more powers,\u2019 urgent measures vs. Covid-19|date=22 March 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 23, 2020, the Senate of the Philippines and the Philippine House of Representatives both held special sessions to discuss the measure.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/senateph/posts/3083188928372034|title=Sspecial session of the Senate to discuss a measure authorizing the President to exercise powers necessary to address the COVID-19 health emergency|date=23 March 2020|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255507-updates-house-special-session-bill-duterte-emergency-powers-coronavirus-march-2020|title=House special session on bill giving Duterte emergency powers for virus outbreak|date=23 March 2020|publisher=Rappler|access-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===== Luzon =====\nOn March 16, President Duterte placed the island of [[Luzon]] under \"enhanced\" community quarantine<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/CNNPhilippines/videos/cnn-philippines-special-coverage-president-rodrigo-duterte-orders-enhanced-commu/515691529377942/|title=CNN PHILIPPINES SPECIAL COVERAGE: President Rodrigo Duterte orders \u2018enhanced community quarantine\u2019 in Luzon|date=16 March 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|work=Facebook|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> that further restricted the movement of people through the suspension of mass public transport and the closure of non-essential establishments. Business Process Outsourcing and export-oriented businesses were allowed to continue operation subject to certain conditions. Relevant government agencies were ordered to provide social amelioration measures.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=16 March 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[San Miguel Corporation]] subsequently announced that its food, fuel, and power generation facilities would continue operation to provide essential services. [[Ramon S. Ang|Vice-Chairman, President and COO Ramon S. Ang]] gave assurances of the company's capability to produce sufficient food supplies and its commitment to continue paying its employees.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.sanmiguel.com.ph/article/smc-assures-its-food-facilities-will-continue-to-operate-outlines-efforts-to-help-fight-covid-19|title=SMC ASSURES ITS FOOD FACILITIES WILL CONTINUE TO OPERATE; OUTLINES EFFORTS TO HELP FIGHT COVID-19|date=16 March 2020|publisher=San Miguel Corporation|access-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The effects of\n\n===== Region I - Ilocos Region =====\nAs of March 14, 2020, there were no confirmed COVID-19 cases in the [[Ilocos Region]]; 10 persons under investigation (PUIs) were admitted, and 25 PUIs were discharged.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/|title=COVID-19 Philippine Cases|date=14 March 2020|publisher=Republic of the Philippines - Department of Health|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====== Province of Ilocos Norte ======\nOn March 13, 2020, [[Ilocos Norte]] [[Matthew Manotoc|Governor Matthew Marcos Manotoc]] issued Executive Order No. 59-20 which suspended classes in private and public institutions indefinitely and mandated the duties of school officials/administrators and parents/guardians, which included the adoption of and participation in alternative measures for course completion.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/MatthewMarcosManotoc/posts/2254794861494403|title=Executive Order No. 59-20, Series of 2020, Office of the Governor, Province of Ilocos Norte|date=13 March 2020|work=Facebook|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\nOn March 14, 2020, he signed Executive Order No. 60-20 which placed the province under community quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/MatthewMarcosManotoc/posts/2255781534729069|title=Executive Order No. 60-20, Series of 2020, Office of the Governor, Province of Ilocos Norte|date=15 March 2020|work=Facebook|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The order activated Task Force Salun-at, which was previously institutionalized under Executive Order No. 51-20.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/MatthewMarcosManotoc/posts/2238629899777566|title=Executive Order No. 51-20, Series of 2020, Office of the Governor, Province of Ilocos Norte|date=20 February 2020|work=Facebook|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Under the provisions of Executive Order No. 60-20, Task Force Salun-at was given authority over the province to deny entry to certain individuals based on criteria specified in the order, and enforce checking of individuals seeking entry and required clearance, endorsement, quarantine, and monitoring. The executive order also included provisions for the:\n* regulation of ports and borders;\n* the preparation of health information forms,\n* personal and public preventive measures,\n* identification of quarantine areas,\n* prohibition of hoarding, reselling, and price spikes, and\n* prohibition of the spreading of fake news.\n\n====== Province of Ilocos Sur ======\nIn the northern Philippine province of [[Ilocos Sur]], [[Ryan Luis Singson|Governor Ryan Luis V. Singson]] issued Executive Order No. 12<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/ryanluisvsingsonofficial/photos/a.238837419489519/3063385213701378/|title=Executive Order No. 12, Series of 2020, Office of the Governor, Province of Ilocos Sur|date=12 March 2020|work=Facebook|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and Executive Order No. 13,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/ryanluisvsingsonofficial/photos/a.238837419489519/3064810423558857/|title=Executive Order No. 13, Series of 2020, Office of the Governor, Province of Ilocos Sur|date=13 March 2020|work=Facebook|access-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> on March 12 and 13, 2020, respectively. The executive orders mandated the suspension of classes in all levels from March 13 to April 12, 2020, as well as the suspension of other school activities that involve the gathering of crowds, at both public and private schools in the province.\n\nOn March 15, the province was placed under community quarantine through Executive Order No. 14<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.facebook.com/ryanluisvsingsonofficial/posts/3070161436357089|title=Executive Order No. 14, Series of 2020, Office of the Governor, Province of Ilocos Sur|date=16 March 2020|work=Facebook|access-date=16 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> which restricted the movement of people to and from Ilocos Sur, mandated the establishment of checkpoints and conditions for transportation and travel, prohibited social gatherings, encouraged flexible/alternative work arrangements or suspension of work, suspended tourism, prohibited hoarding, delineated rules for business establishments, and imposed curfew.\n\n===In Europe===\n==== Italy ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy}}\n[[File:Emergenza coronavirus (49496308758).jpg|thumb|right|[[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]] volunteers carrying out health checks at the [[Guglielmo Marconi Airport]] in [[Bologna]]]]\n\nThe outbreak was confirmed to have spread to Italy on 31 January 2020, when two Chinese tourists tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 in Rome.<ref name=\"Corriere_20Jan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_30/coronavirus-italia-corona-9d6dc436-4343-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml|title=Coronavirus: Primi due casi in Italia|date=31 January 2020|trans-title=Coronavirus: First two cases in Italy|website=Corriere della sera|language=it|accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> In response, the Italian government suspended all flights to and from China and declared a state of emergency, with Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] stating that Italy is the first EU country to take this precautionary measure.<ref name=\"thelocal-flight\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200131/italy-suspends-all-china-flights-after-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-rome/|title=Italy suspends all China flights as coronavirus cases confirmed in Rome|date=31 January 2020|website=THELOCAL|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> On 31 January, the [[Council of Ministers of Italy|Italian Council of Ministers]] appointed [[Angelo Borrelli]], head of the [[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]], as Special Commissioner for the COVID-19 Emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://tg24.sky.it/politica/approfondimenti/angelo-borrelli-chi-e.html |title=Chi \u00e8 Angelo Borrelli, nominato Commissario per l'emergenza coronavirus |website=tg24.sky.it |language=it |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fanpage.it/politica/coronavirus-angelo-borrelli-nominato-commissario-straordinario-ecco-chi-e/|title=Coronavirus, Angelo Borrelli commissario straordinario: potr\u00e0 anche requisire gli hotel|website=Fanpage}}</ref> A unassociated cluster of [[COVID-19]] cases was later further detected starting with 16 confirmed cases in [[Lombardy]] on 21 February,<ref name=\"ThomReut_IT_16cluster_21Feb\">{{cite news|last1=Anzolin|first1=Elisa|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI|title=coronavirus pandemic grows in northern Italy, 16 cases reported in one day|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=21 February 2020|url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped -->|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221225322/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI|archivedate=21 February 2020|agency=[[Thomson Reuters]]|last2=Amante|first2=Angelo|url-access=<!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> an additional 60 cases on 22 February, and Italy's first deaths reported on the same day.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe Ministry of Health announced new guidelines for reporting cases on 27 February in response to the previous blanket testing that caused case numbers to surge and inflamed public panic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/28/news/_polmoniti_anomale_a_meta_gennaio_cosi_e_nato_il_focolaio_di_codogno_-249759796/|title=Coronavirus, polmoniti anomale a met\u00e0 gennaio: \"Cos\u00ec \u00e8 nato il focolaio di Codogno\"|date=27 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> It would no longer report asymptomatic cases (swabs taken from patients which tested positive but were not showing symptoms) which counted as 40 to 50% of all reported cases at the time. These people would undergo isolation at home and would be followed up with new tests until they were negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/28/news/cambia_il_metodo_di_conteggio_esclusi_i_positivi_asintomatici-249765660/|title=Cambia il metodo di conteggio: esclusi i positivi asintomatici|date=27 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory/italy-virus-count-methods-agencys-urging-69254949|title=Italy blasts virus panic as it eyes new testing criteria|publisher=ABC News|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the [[Council of Ministers of Italy|Italian Council of Ministers]] announced a new decree law to contain the outbreak, including quarantining more than 50,000 people from 11 different municipalities in [[northern Italy]].<ref name=\"AutoDW-201\"/> Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] said \"In the outbreak areas, entry and exit will not be provided. Suspension of work activities and sport events has already been ordered in those areas.\"<ref name=\"AutoDW-202\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-203\"/> Punishments for violating of the lockdown range from a fine of 206 euros to 3 months imprisonment.<ref name=\"AutoDW-204\"/> [[Italian army|Italian military]] and law enforcement agencies were instructed to secure and implement the lockdown.<ref name=\"AutoDW-205\"/>\n\nOn 3 March, Chinese authorities reported that on March first and second, eight virus victims who had returned to the county of Qingtian, in East China's Zhejiang province, were suffering from the virus. All eight appear to have acquired Covid-19 in the northern town of [[Bergamo, Italy]], a virus-ravaged municipality, where they had worked at a restaurant, Qingtian officials said. Chinese authorities called these \"backflow cases\" \u2014 virus carriers who contract the disease outside China, then bring it back to their homeland.<ref>Flynn Murphy, Zhang Erchi and Ye Zhanqi, [https://www.caixinglobal.com/2020-03-03/china-faces-growing-virus-threat-from-outside-the-country-101523601.html \"China Faces Growing Virus Threat From Outside the Country\"], ''Caixin'', 3 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, the Italian government ordered the full closure of all schools and universities nationwide as Italy reached 100 deaths. Additionally, all major sporting events, including Serie A football matches, would be held behind closed doors until April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Palermo|first=Angela Giuffrida Lorenzo Tondo in|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/04/italy-orders-closure-of-schools-and-universities-due-to-coronavirus|title=Italy orders closure of all schools and universities due to coronavirus|date=4 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|last2=Beaumont|first2=Peter|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 9 March, all sport was suspended completely for at least one month.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/51808683 | title=Coronavirus: All sport in Italy suspended because of outbreak| work=BBC Sport| date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{main|2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown}}\nOn 21 February, at least ten towns in the Lombardy and [[Veneto]] regions of Italy, with a total population of 50,000, were locked down in quarantine procedure following an outbreak in [[Codogno]] in Lombardy. Police mandated a curfew closing all public buildings and controlling access through police checkpoints to the so-called 'red zone' which is enforced by penalties for violations ranging from a \u20ac206 fine to three months of imprisonment against trespassers who are not health or supply workers.<ref name=\"AutoDW-204\"/> The government of Giuseppe Conte said that sending in the armed forces to enforce the lockdown was a possibility.<ref name=\"AutoDW-205\"/> The governor of [[Basilicata]], [[Vito Bardi]], instituted a mandatory 14-day quarantine for people arriving from areas in northern Italy affected by the outbreak on 24 February.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Feb2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/|title=Coronavirus, quarto morto, \u00e8 un 84enne di Bergamo. Sette regioni coinvolte per 30 milioni di italiani|date=24 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> On the same day, 500 extra police officers were assigned to patrol the quarantined areas in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] and Veneto.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Feb2\"/>\n\nOn the morning of 8 March 2020, Conte said that much of Italy's northern territories, including Milan and Venice, would be quarantined within their region.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Horowitz |first1=Jason |title=Italy Locks Down Much of the Country's North Over the Coronavirus |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/07/world/europe/coronavirus-italy.html|accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=7 March 2020}}</ref> Conte said the country was locking down all of the populous Lombardy region, with movement restrictions applying to about 16 million people.<ref name=Italia>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/italy-coronavirus-milan-lombardy-lockdowns/2020/03/07/403fcea2-60b3-11ea-ac50-18701e14e06d_story.html To contain coronavirus, Italy will restrict movement across much of its northern region, including the city of Milan], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Chico Harlan and Stefano Pitrelli, 7 March 2020. Retrieved 8 March 2020.</ref> This will be the most aggressive response taken in any region beyond China, and will paralyse the wealthiest parts of the country as Italy attempts to constrain the rapid spread of the disease.<ref name=Italia/> On 8 March 2020, there have been 7,375 confirmed cases, and 366 deaths in Italy.<ref name=JHMap/>\n\nOn the evening of 9 March 2020, the quarantine was expanded to all of Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51810673|title=Coronavirus: Italy extends strict quarantine measures nationwide|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==== France ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\nOn 24 January 2020, the first case of COVID-19 in France was confirmed in [[Bordeaux]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jacob |first1=Etienne |title=Coronavirus: trois premiers cas confirm\u00e9s en France, deux d'entre eux vont bien |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/sciences/coronavirus-trois-premiers-cas-confirmes-en-france-20200124 |website=Le Figaro.fr |accessdate=7 March 2020 |language=fr |date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, [[President Macron]] announced a nationwide lockdown for 15 days starting on 17 March midday, through a decree prohibiting all but essential outings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-france-lockdown-cases-update-covid-19-macron-a9405136.html|title=France imposes 15-day lockdown as part of emergency coronavirus response|date=16 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n====Germany====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany}}\nAt the end of January 2020, the first cases occurred in Bavaria in direct connection with the outbreak in Wuhan, China. After initial stagnation, several other cases were reported in different locations. During carnival in February, Heinsberg in Northrhine Westfalia was most affected, and case numbers steadily increased. By the second week of March, all federal states were affected and the first fatality was reported.<ref name=\"aa\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/blob/2294930/33e99dc559cfe3dbda8e7ae65b39c3be/ncov-data.pdf |title=COVID 19 |date=2020-03-27 |work=Gesundheitsdienst, Ausw\u00e4rtiges Amt |access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\nAs of March 28, 2020 the incidence was highest in the city state of Hamburg, followed by Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg and Bavaria.<ref name=\"rki\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rki.de/DE/Content/InfAZ/N/Neuartiges_Coronavirus/Situationsberichte/2020-03-28-en.pdfFile |title= Coronavirus Disease 2019  |date=2020-03-27 |work=Daily Situation Report of the Robert Koch Institute}}</ref>\nThe [[Robert Koch Institute]] recommended an initial strategy of containment, until more cases would occur than could be traced back to an known case. The next phase of the epidemic, namely community transmission, was assumed to have begun first in Heinsberg, where a strategy of protection of vulnerable groups was adopted.<ref name=\"aa\"/>\n\n==== Greece ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Greece}}\nOn 26 February, the first case in Greece was confirmed, a 38-year-old woman from [[Thessaloniki]] who had recently visited [[Northern Italy]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-greece-idUSKCN20K1IA|title=Greece confirms first coronavirus case|date=26 February 2020|work=Reuters|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Within the next days, health and state authorities issued precautionary guidelines and recommendations, while measures up to that point were taken locally and included the closure of schools and the suspension of cultural events in the affected areas (particularly [[Elis (regional unit)|Ilia]], [[Achaea]] and [[Zakynthos]]).<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsit.gr/ellada/koronoios-14-akoma-krousmata-stin-ellad/2988717/|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: 14 \u03b1\u03ba\u03cc\u03bc\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1!|last=|first=|date=|website=www.newsit.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> Various municipalities around the country began disinfecting schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ieidiseis.gr/ellada/item/36906-koronoios-stin-ellada-proliptikes-apolymanseis-se-dimosia-ktiria-apo-ton-dimo-iliou|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03c0\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03ac\u03bd\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf \u0399\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5|last=iEidiseis|website=www.ieidiseis.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The Greek [[National Public Health Organization (Greece)|National Public Health Organization]] (NPHO), in collaboration with local authorities and doctors, is tracking and testing everyone who came in close contact with the confirmed carriers.<ref>{{cite Web|url=https://www.onmed.gr/ygeia-eidhseis/story/382322/koronoios-stin-patra-to-enato-kroysma|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03b1\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0388\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03b2\u03b5\u03b2\u03b1\u03b9\u03c9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1|website=www.onmed.gr|language=el}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ant1news.gr/ygeia-periballon/article/561722/koronoios-deka-ta-kroysmata-stin-ellada|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0394\u03ad\u03ba\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|last=|first=|date=|website=antenna.gr|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nBy 10 March, with 89 confirmed cases and no deaths in the country,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.gr/news/ellada/story/210621/koronoios-stin-ellada-anakoinothikan-pente-nea-kroysmata|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03ce\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd \u03c0\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5 \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1|last=|first=|date=10 March 2020|website=cnn.gr|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> the government decided to suspend the operation of all schools, universities, daycare centers and all other educational establishments nationwide and then, on 13 March, to close down all cafes, bars, museums, shopping centres, sports facilities and restaurants in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/news/44308-10-03-20-prosorini-apagorefsi-tis-ekpaideftikis-leitourgias-olon-ton-ekpaideftikon-domon|title=\u03a5\u03a0\u039f\u03a5\u03a1\u0393\u0395\u0399\u039f \u03a0\u0391\u0399\u0394\u0395\u0399\u0391\u03a3 & \u0398\u03a1\u0397\u03a3\u039a\u0395\u03a5\u039c\u0391\u03a4\u03a9\u039d - 10-03-20 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03cc\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03b4\u03bf\u03bc\u03ce\u03bd|last=|first=|date=|website=www.minedu.gov.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capital.gr/epikairotita/3437285/sta-190-sunolika-ta-krousmata-stin-ellada-kleinoun-emporika-kentra-kafe-mpar|title=\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1 190 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 - \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03ba\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1, \u03ba\u03b1\u03c6\u03ad, \u03bc\u03c0\u03b1\u03c1|last=Capital.gr|website=Capital.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On 16 March, all retail shops were also closed and all services in all areas of religious worship of any religion or dogma were suspended. Supermarkets, pharmacies, food outlets that offer take-away and delivery only as well as some other businesses remained open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/koinonia/koronoios-kleinoyn-ta-emporika-katastimata-se-karantina-osoi-erchontai-apo-exoteriko.7603146.html|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 - \u03a3\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u03b9 \u03ad\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03b5\u03be\u03c9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc|last=|first=|date=|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kathimerini.gr/1069449/article/epikairothta/politikh/anastellontai-oles-oi-8rhskeytikes-leitoyrgies-me-apofash-ths-kyvernhshs|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03b8\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c6\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c5\u03b2\u03ad\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 {{!}} Kathimerini|last=|first=|date=|website=www.kathimerini.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> On 18 and 19 March, the government announced a series of economic measures of more than 10 billion euros to support the economy, businesses and employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/oikonomia/94785_koronoios-ta-metra-gia-ergazomenoys-ki-epiheiriseis|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03cc\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b9 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2|language=el|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the Greek authorities announced significant restrictions on all nonessential transport and movement across the country, starting from 6 a.m. on 23 March. Movement outside the house is permitted only for specific reasons that include moving to or from the workplace, shopping for food or medicine, going to the bank, visiting a doctor or assisting a person in need of help and walking a pet or exercising outside individually or in pairs. Citizens leaving their home are required to carry their police ID or passport, as well as some type of attestation depending on the purpose of travel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250917/article/ekathimerini/news/full-lockdown-in-effect-from-monday-to-curb-coronavirus|title=Full lockdown in effect from Monday to curb coronavirus {{!}} Kathimerini|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Spain ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain}}\nOn 31 January 2020, the first case was confirmed when a tourist tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 in [[La Gomera]], Spain.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Linde |first1=Pablo |title=Sanidad confirma en La Gomera el primer caso de coronavirus en Espa\u00f1a |url=https://elpais.com/sociedad/2020/01/31/actualidad/1580509404_469734.html |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |accessdate=8 March 2020 |language=es |date=1 February 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, due to the increased number of cases, Spanish Prime Minister [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez]] declared a [[State of Alarm|state of alarm]], placing all citizens in quarantine except for those working in healthcare or other vital activities, closing all non-critical businesses, and only allowing citizens to go outside for activities such as grocery shopping or walking a pet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtve.es/noticias/20200313/pedro-sanchez-declara-estado-alarma-nacional/2009974.shtml|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez declara el estado de alarma nacional|last=GRANDE|first=ROC\u00cdO GIL|date=2020-03-13|website=RTVE.es|language=es|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==== Switzerland ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Switzerland}}\nOn 28 February, Switzerland's [[Federal Council (Switzerland)|Federal Council]] announced an immediate ban on all public and private events involving more than 1000 participants.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/politics/coronavirus_switzerland-bans-events-with-more-than-1-000-people/45585378|title=Switzerland bans major public events to slow spread of virus|author=|website=[[Swissinfo]]|language=en|access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\nOn 24 March 2020, the United Kingdom brought in \"some of the most far-reaching curbs on personal freedom ever introduced\" in peacetime, including a three-week lockdown of the country. This included a ban on public gatherings of more than two people (excluding those one lives with) and the closing down of all non-essential businesses.<ref>{{cite news |title=UK brings in strict curbs on life to fight virus |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52014472 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===In the Americas===\n==== United States ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\nOn 28 January 2020, the American government made public the approach to COVID-19 testing which it developed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenberg |first1=Jon |last2=Knight |first2=Victoria |title=Mostly False: Joe Biden stated on March 15, 2020 in a Democratic primary debate: \"The World Health Organization offered the testing kits that they have available and to give it to us now. We refused them. We did not want to buy them.\" |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/16/joe-biden/biden-falsely-says-trump-administration-rejected-w/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[Politifact]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Despite doing so, the United States proceeded to have a slow start in testing, which obscured the true extent of the outbreak at the time.<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16>{{cite news |last1=Whoriskey |first1=Peter |last2=Satija |first2=Neena |title=How U.S. coronavirus testing stalled: Flawed tests, red tape and resistance to using the millions of tests produced by the WHO |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/16/cdc-who-coronavirus-tests/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=WangMarch22>{{cite news |last1=Wang |first1=Jessica |last2=Huth |first2=Lindsay |last3=Umlauf |first3=Taylor |last4=Wang |first4=Elbert |last5=McKay |first5=Betsy |title=How the CDC's Restrictive Testing Guidelines Hid the Coronavirus Epidemic |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-the-cdcs-restrictive-testing-guidelines-hid-the-coronavirus-epidemic-11584882001 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archivedate=22 March 2020 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=22 March 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.today/tp9HA}}</ref> The American federal government produced 160,000 test kits in February, but many were found to be defective and thus not utilized.<ref name=\"WhoriskeyMarch16\"/> Although academic laboratories and hospitals had developed their own tests, they were not allowed to use them until February 29, when the FDA started issuing approvals for them and private companies.<ref name=\"WhoriskeyMarch16\"/> Furthermore, restrictive criteria on who would be eligible for COVID-19 testing were put in place until early March. Those eligible were (a) people who had recently traveled to certain countries affected by the outbreak, or (b) people with respiratory illness serious enough to require hospitalization, or (c) people who have been in contact with a person confirmed to have COVID-19. Only on March{{nbsp}}5 did the CDC relax the criteria to allow doctors discretion to decide who would be eligible for tests.<ref name=WangMarch22/> By February 27, fewer than 4,000 tests were conducted in the United States, reported ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref name=WhoriskeyMarch16/> By March 13, the number was fewer than 14,000, reported ''[[The Atlantic]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khazan |first1=Olga |title=The 4 Key Reasons the U.S. Is So Behind on Coronavirus Testing |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/03/why-coronavirus-testing-us-so-delayed/607954/ |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, President [[Donald Trump]] issued a proclamation limiting entry into the United States, as immigrants or nonimmigrants, of all aliens who were physically present within the People's Republic of China, excluding the Special Administrative Regions of Hong Kong and Macau, during the 14-day period preceding their entry or attempted entry into the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/proclamation-suspension-entry-immigrants-nonimmigrants-persons-pose-risk-transmitting-2019-novel-coronavirus/|title=Proclamation on Suspension of Entry as Immigrants and Nonimmigrants of Persons who Pose a Risk of Transmitting 2019 Novel Coronavirus|website=The White House}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Pacific Northwest]] state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]], the first six confirmed deaths in the United States were reported in late February 2020, with two deaths and an outbreak at a [[Life Care Centers of America#Kirkland, Washington COVID-19 outbreak|Life Care Centers of America]] [[elderly care]] in [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]], Washington, affecting residents, staff, firefighters, and nursing students.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-29/coronavirus-california-spread-health-officials|title=California sees third case of 'community spread' coronavirus as first U.S. death is reported near Seattle|date=29 February 2020|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/news/2020/03/02/coronavirus-travel-italy-japan-asia-trip-plans-in-limbo/4891579002/ Making travel plans? How coronavirus fear is spreading and putting trips in limbo], ''[[USA Today]]'', David Oliver, Sara M Moniuszko, Dawn Gilbertson, Hannah Yasharoff, Curtis Tate, and Morgan Hines, 2 March 2020. Retrieved 2 March 2020.</ref> Washington governor [[Jay Inslee]] declared a state of emergency on 28 February after a man there died of COVID-19, the first such reported death in the United States. Florida governor [[Ron DeSantis]] also declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/coronavirus-cases-unknown-origin-found-west-coast-69301250|title=Washington governor declares state of emergency over virus|publisher=ABC News|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Leins|first=Casey|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/articles/2020-03-02/washington-florida-governors-declare-state-of-emergency-for-coronavirus|title=Washington, Florida Governors Declare State of Emergency for Coronavirus|date=2 March 2020|work=US News and World Report|access-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/02/29/coronavirus-outbreak-live-updates-oregon-case-italy-level-3-california/4904296002/|title=Washington state declares emergency after first patient dies from coronavirus in US|date=29 February 2020|work=USA Today}}</ref> On 4 March, California governor [[Gavin Newsom]] declared a state of emergency after the first death within state borders, in addition to 53 confirmed cases within the state.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freiman |first1=Jordan |title=California governor declares State of Emergency |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/coronavirus-outbreak-death-toll-us-infections-latest-news-updates-2020-03-04/ |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMajor US corporations have imposed employee travel restrictions. Twitter \"suspend[ed] all non-critical business travel and events\". Facebook cancelled its [[Facebook F8|F8 developer conference]]. [[Goldman Sachs]] cancelled all \"non-essential\" travel and put in place specific restrictions on travel to China, South Korea, Italy, and Iran. [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], who confirmed an employee in the Seattle area tested positive for COVID-19,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/amazon/amazon-employee-in-seattle-has-tested-positive-for-illness-caused-by-coronavirus/|title=Amazon employee in Seattle has tested positive for illness caused by coronavirus|last=Ramano|first=Benjamin|date=3 March 2020|website=The Seattle Times|url-status=live|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref> banned nonessential employee travel. [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] closed its Oregon headquarters and its European headquarters in Amsterdam \"out of an abundance of caution\". As required by regulation, large American banks are reviewing emergency plans to ensure that they can continue to operate if conditions worsen; contingency plans include having employees work from their homes, transferring staff to backup offices and even sending staff to offices in other cities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/coronavirus-covid-19-twitter-amazon-nike-google-offices-deep-clean-travel-ban-092211063.html|title=Twitter, Amazon.com, Nike and more take emergency coronavirus precautions|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> Some companies, including [[Microsoft]], [[GitHub]], and [[Square, Inc.]], have also encouraged employees to work from home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/business/article/Coronavirus-pushes-big-Bay-Area-companies-towards-15105962.php|title=Coronavirus: Microsoft, Square, Twitter encourage employees to work from home|date=5 March 2020|website=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOver a dozen schools in the [[Seattle]] area cancelled classes on 3 March for disinfection and other precautionary measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/coronavirus-prompts-dozen-schools-washington-state-close-others-weigh-options-n1145496|title=More schools are closing because of coronavirus. Will that be the norm?|publisher=NBC News|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> On {{date|6 March}}, the [[University of Washington]] cancelled in-person classes. The Seattle-based university is home to 50,000 students.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0362-4331| last1 = Baker| first1 = Mike| last2 = Hartocollis| first2 = Anemona| last3 = Weise| first3 = Karen| title = First U.S. Colleges Close Classrooms as Virus Spreads. More Could Follow.| work = The New York Times| accessdate = 2020-03-10| date = 2020-03-06| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/06/us/coronavirus-college-campus-closings.html}}</ref> Multiple public and private schools outside New York City have closed as a result of the virus, including the [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] public school districts of [[Hastings-on-Hudson, New York|Hastings-on-Hudson]], [[Mount Vernon, New York|Mount Vernon]], [[Yonkers Public Schools|Yonkers]], etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/ny-hastings-on-hudson-schools-closed-coronavirus-20200305-6n2i74b73be2bpjgxsgxrlwwoi-story.html|title=Hastings-on-Hudson, Mount Vernon schools close to sanitize after coronavirus contact|first=JOHN|last=ANNESE|website=nydailynews.com}}</ref> All schools within the [[Elk Grove Unified School District]] in the [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] area shut down on 7 March after a case of the virus appeared in [[Elk Grove, California|Elk Grove]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.egusd.net/pressroom/2020/03/07/media-statement-elk-grove-unified-closes-school-cancels-classes-and-cancels-student-related-activities-effective-march-7-to-march-13-2020/|title=Media Statement: Elk Grove Unified Closes School, Cancels Classes and Cancels Student-Related Activities Effective 7 March to 13 March 2020. {{!}} NEWSROOM|website=blogs.egusd.net|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 8 March 2020, the number of deaths in the US had risen to 22, with over 500 cases reported.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/world/coronavirus-news.html In U.S., Cases of Coronavirus Cross 500, and Deaths Rise to 22], ''[[New York Times]]'', 9 March 2020. Retrieved 9 March 2020.</ref>\n\nSome Americans seem resentful at being asked to worry, and believe that COVID-19 appears no worse than the flu.<ref name=\"MarketWatch, so everyone is overreacting, right?, 9 March 2020\">\n[https://www.marketwatch.com/story/coronavirus-vs-the-flu-its-just-like-other-viruses-and-we-should-go-about-our-normal-business-right-wrong-heres-why-2020-03-09 \u2018We\u2019re going to have more deaths\u2019: Influenza kills more people than the coronavirus so everyone is overreacting, right? Wrong \u2014 and here\u2019s why], ''MarketWatch'', Quentin Fottrell, 9 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==== Costa Rica ====\n\nSince the start of the pandemic, the Ministry of Health, together with the Government, were in charge of informing the general population through a daily press conference. By March 6, the first confirmed case of COVID-19 is registered after several results obtained by INCIENSA (Costa Rican Institute of Research and Teaching in Nutrition and Health). The 49-year-old American woman was isolated, along with her husband in a San Jos\u00e9 lodging. There were 2 previous suspected cases under investigation. The positive patient arrived with her husband on Sunday, March 1 without symptoms, at the Juan Santamar\u00eda airport, they visited Alajuela and Puntarenas, so investigations were carried out from these areas to follow up on contacts, as well as 152 people traveling on the flight that brought them to the country.<ref>[https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1555-caso-confirmado-por-covid-19-en-costa-rica 'First case confirmed in Costa Rica'], Costarrican Ministry of Health, March 6\"</ref>\n\nOn March 9, Due to the nine confirmed cases of COVID-19, the Ministry of Health in coordination with the National Emergency Commission (CNE)  reported that from March 10, events and concentration activities are canceled massive, both free and paid, while teleworking for public institutions is instructed through the Presidential Directive.<ref>[https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1560-gobierno-cancela-eventos-masivos-e-instruye-teletrabajo-para-sector-publico 'Government cancels massive events and instructs telework for the public sector'], Costarrican Ministry of Health, March 9</ref>\n\nThe President Carlos Alvarado and the Minister of Health, Daniel Salas announced, on March 12, preventive closings to educational centers at risk, the reduction in 50% of the approved capacity of public meeting spaces and suspension of trips abroad for public employees. A telephone line is created for inquiries about COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1566-segunda-fase-de-atencion-alerta-amarilla-covid-19-cierre-preventivo-a-centros-educativos-en-riesgo-reduccion-en-50-capacidad-de-espacios-de-reunion-y-suspension-de-viajes-al-extranjero-para-empleados-pubicos|title=Segunda fase de atenci\u00f3n alerta amarilla COVID-19: Cierre preventivo a centros educativos en riesgo, reducci\u00f3n en 50% capacidad de espacios de reuni\u00f3n y suspensi\u00f3n de viajes al extranjero para empleados p\u00fablicos |trans-title=Second phase of attention yellow alert COVID-19: Preventive closure to schools at risk, 50% reduction in meeting space capacity and suspension of trips abroad for public employees |website=www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, the Ministry of Health made the decision to instruct a total lockdown placing all citizens in quarantine except for those working in healthcare and delivery restaurant and food services. The closure of bars, clubs and casinos and the amusement park was informed. By this date 35 confirmed cases of COVID-19 are registered in the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1571-ante-covid-19-lineamientos-se-endurecen-con-el-cierre-total-de-bares-discotecas-y-casinos|title=Ante COVID-19: lineamientos se endurecen con el cierre total de bares, discotecas y casinos|website=www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, The Government declares a state of National Emergency, prevents the arrival of foreigners and lessons are suspended in all schools. Costa Ricans and residents who entered the country will have to carry out mandatory preventive isolation for 14 days. 41 cases are confirmed.<ref>[https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1572-gobierno-declara-estado-de-emergencia-nacional-impide-llegada-de-extranjeros-y-se-suspende-lecciones-en-todos-los-centros-educativos-del-pais National Emergency], Ministry of Heath, March 16</ref>\n\nThe first death of a patient confirmed by COVID-19 is recorded by March 18. This is an 87-year-old man who was hospitalized in intensive care at the Alajuela Hospital.<ref>[https://www.ministeriodesalud.go.cr/index.php/centro-de-prensa/noticias/741-noticias-2020/1575-primer-fallecido-por-covid-19 First deceased by COVID-19], March 18, Ministry of Heath</ref>\n\nBy March 31, were registered 8 in intensive care and 347 people were infected. 4 people recovered.\n\n===In Oceania===\n====Australia====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia}}\n\n====Fiji====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Fiji}}\n\nAt the beginning of February, the Government of Fiji announced a travel ban to China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/fiji-to-close-boarders-to-foreign-nationals-amidst-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Fiji toughens on border entry amidst coronavirus concerns|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> As the disease started spreading to other countries, Fiji extended the travel ban to Italy, Iran and South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.rnz.co.nz/article/d796c6bb-8ea3-408f-9b64-a9a17609b4b9|title=Coronavirus: Fiji extends travel ban amid growing concerns|website=amp.rnz.co.nz|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on 19 March, Fiji confirmed its first case of COVID-19 in Lautoka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijivillage.com/news/COVID-19-patient-is-a-27-year-old-flight-attendant-who-had-recent-travel-history-to-USA-and-NZ---Dr-Sahukhan-4x8rf5/|title=COVID-19 patient is a 27-year-old flight attendant who had recent travel history to USA and NZ - Dr. Sahukhan|last=Fijivillage|website=www.fijivillage.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> As a precautionary measure, the Government of Fiji announced the lockdown of the city until 7 April 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/covid-19-lautoka-schools-closed-until-further-notice/|title=COVID-19: Lautoka schools closed until further notice|website=FijiTimes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and the travel ban was further extended to the United States and the whole of Europe including the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/pm-announces-major-restrictions-including-closure-of-some-services-due-to-covid-19/|title=PM announces major restrictions due to COVID-19|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Later on 2 April, the Government announced a lockdown of Suva, after confirmed cases in the capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/news/covid-19/fiji-confirms-latest-cases-of-covid-19/|title=Nabua couple are latest COVID-19 patients, Suva in lockdown from tomorrow|last=News|first=Indra Singh Manager|website=Fiji Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAs the cases rose, [[Prime Minister of Fiji|Prime Minister]] [[Frank Bainimarama|Voreqe Bainimarama]] announced a nationwide curfew from 8pm to 5am and social gatherings was banned. Schools and non-essential services was closed and the public was advised to stay at home and practice good hygiene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fijitimes.com/nationwide-curfew-to-come-into-effect-from-sunday/|title=COVID-19: Nationwide curfew to come into effect from Monday|website=FijiTimes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n====New Zealand====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Zealand}}\nOn 28 January, the Ministry of Health set up the National Health Coordination Centre (NHCC) in response to the outbreak. On 3 February, the New Zealand Government announced that foreign travellers who left from China would be denied entry to New Zealand, with only New Zealand citizens and permanent residents and their family being allowed to enter.\n\nNew Zealand confirmed its first case of Covid-19 on 28 February, a New Zealand citizen in his 60s who had recently visited Iran. The travel ban was extended to include Iran on the same day.\n\n17 March: Health Minister David Clark announced that the Government would deport foreign tourists who flout self-quarantine restrictions. Immigration New Zealand placed two foreign tourists into forced quarantine for defying Government requirements to self-quarantine for two weeks. Finance Minister Grant Robertson announced a NZ$12.1 billion Covid-19 business package. Logan Park High School in Dunedin closed for 48 hours after one of its students tested positive for the coronavirus.\n\n18 March: The Royal New Zealand Returned and Services' Association announced that all Anzac Day services, scheduled for 25 April, would be cancelled.\n\n19 March: The government required the cancellation of mass indoor events with more than 100 people. Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern announced the closure of New Zealand's borders to all but New Zealand citizens and residents, with effect after 11:59 pm on Thursday night.\n\n21 March: Local councils in New Zealand's main centres announced the closures of public facilities including swimming pools, libraries, recreation centres, community centres, art galleries, and museums.\n\n23 March: Prime Minister Ardern raised the Covid-19 alert level from two to three and announced the closure of all schools beginning on that day. The Government also announced that they would raise the national alert level to four at 11:59pm on 25 March, which would lead to a nationwide lockdown, for a period of four weeks. While all sporting matches and events as well as non-essential services such as pools, bars, cafes, restaurants, playgrounds are required to close in 48 hours, essential services such as supermarkets, petrol stations, and health services will remain open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=12319029|title=Covid 19 coronavirus alert 3: New Zealand to move to alert 4 lockdown for next four weeks - Jacinda Ardern says schools closed, essential services only|first=Derek Cheng Derek Cheng is a political reporter for the New Zealand Herald|last=derek.cheng@nzme.co.nz|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|via=www.nzherald.co.nz}}</ref>\n\n===In Africa===\n==== South Africa ====\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa}}\n{{multiple image\n | width = 160\n | footer = [[Greenmarket Square]] in [[Cape Town]], South Africa seven days before (left) and on the first day (right) of the COVID 19 national lockdown. After the lockdown the [[market stall]] traders that normally setup on the square everyday are not present and only people exempt from the lockdown (security personnel and municipal employees) can be seen. \n | image1 = Greenmarket square 20200320.jpg\n | alt1 = Greenmarket Square as it normally appears with many market stalls, seven days before the lockdown.\n | caption1 = \n | image2 =  Greenmarket Square 20200327.jpg\n | alt2 = On the first day of the lockdown only people exempt from the lockdown (security personnel and sanitation workers) can be seen.\n | caption2 = \n}}\n[[President of South Africa|President]] [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] declared that South Africa would undergo a national lockdown, for a period of 21 days, from 26 March to 16 April 2020. This drastic measure was intended to help keep the viral infection rate as low as possible and save lives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-23-south-africa-on-lockdown-from-thursday/|title=National Address: South Africa on lockdown from Thursday|first=Cyril|last=Ramaphosa|website=Daily Maverick|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal-inline|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]] \n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=JHMap>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by Johns Hopkins CSSE |url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd4029942