6|ARG}}''' |scoreB ='''59'''\n|Q1 =6\u2013'''20''' |Q2 ='''7'''\u20136 |Q3 ='''17'''\u201312 |Q4 ='''19'''\u201311 |OT=3\u2013'''10'''\n|report =[http://www.fiba.com/americas/u16women/2017/1106/Colombia-Argentina Boxscore]\n|points1 = [[Stephanny Orozco|Orozco]] 15\n|points2 = [[Florencia Chagas|Chagas]] 20\n|rebounds1 = [[Laura Ayala|Ayala]], [[Daniela Gonzalez|Gonzalez]] 9\n|rebounds2 = [[Florencia Chagas|Chagas]] 20\n|assist1 = [[Maria Diaz|Diaz]] 2\n|assist2 = [[Victoria Gauna|Gauna]] 5\n|referee = Americo Rodriguez (VEN), Gina Denise Cross (USA), Natalia Cuello Cuello (DOM)\n}}\n\n===Final===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#ffffd0 |date=11 June 2017 |time=20:30 |place=[[CeNARD|Centro Nacional de Alto Rendimiento Deportivo]], [[Buenos Aires]]\n|teamA = {{bkwu-rt|16|CAN}} |scoreA =46\n|teamB = '''{{bkwu|16|USA}}''' |scoreB ='''91'''\n|Q1 =21\u2013'''27''' |Q2 =4\u2013'''23''' |Q3 =10\u2013'''18''' |Q4 =11\u2013'''23'''\n|report =[http://www.fiba.com/americas/u16women/2017/1106/Canada-USA Boxscore]\n|points1 = [[Merissah Russell|Russell]] 12\n|points2 = [[Azzi Fudd|Fudd]] 18\n|rebounds1 = [[Brynn Ann Masikewich|Masikewich]] 9\n|rebounds2 = [[Jordan Horston|Horston]], [[Aliyah Boston|Boston]] 6\n|assist1 = [[Donna Ntambue|Ntambue]] 2\n|assist2 = [[Jordan Horston|Horston]] 4\n|referee = Andres Gaston Bartel Maina (URU), Alejandra Gaytan Mota (MEX), Carlos Peralta (ECU)\n}}\n\n== Awards ==\n{{winners|bkwu|16|2017 FIBA Under-16 Women's<br />Americas Championship Winners|USA|4th}}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center; margin:auto\"\n![[Most Valuable Player]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Aliyah Boston]]\n|}\n\n==Final ranking==\n{| class=\"infobox bordered\"\n|-\n|width=10px bgcolor=\"#cfc\"| || Qualify for the [[2018 FIBA Under-17 Women's Basketball World Cup]].\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n! width=50|Rank\n! width=175|Team\n! width=50|Record\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| {{Gold1}}\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|USA}}\n|5\u20130\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| {{Silver2}}\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|CAN}}\n|4\u20131\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| {{Bronze3}}\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|ARG}}\n|3\u20132\n|- bgcolor=ccffcc\n| 4\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|COL}}\n|2\u20133\n|-\n| 5\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|MEX}}\n|3\u20132\n|-\n| 6\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|VEN}}\n|2\u20133\n|-\n| 7\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|PUR}}\n|1\u20134\n|-\n| 8\n|align=left|{{bkwu|16|DOM}}\n|0\u20135\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fiba.com/americas/u16women/2017 Official website]\n{{International youth basketball (Women)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:FIBA}}\n[[Category: FIBA Americas Under-16 Championship for Women]]\n[[Category:2017 in women's basketball]]\n[[Category:2016\u201317 in North American basketball]]\n[[Category:2016\u201317 in South American basketball]]\n[[Category:2016\u201317 in Argentine basketball]]\n[[Category: International women's basketball competitions hosted by Argentina]]\n[[Category: Youth sport in Argentina]]\n[[Category: Sports competitions in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category: June 2017 sports events in South America]]\n[[Category: Sport in Buenos Aires|2017]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Maria Diaz", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_FIBA_Under-16_Women%27s_Americas_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Mercedes-Benz E-Class", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = 2019 Mercedes-Benz E220d SE Automatic 2.0 Front.jpg\n| name = Mercedes-Benz E-Class\n| manufacturer = [[Daimler-Benz]] (1993\u20131998)<br>[[DaimlerChrysler]] (1998\u20132007)<br>[[Daimler AG]] (2007\u2013present)<br>[[Magna Steyr]] (4MATIC models only, 1996\u20132009)\n| production = 1953\u2013present\n| class = [[Executive car]] ([[E-segment|E]])\n| layout = [[Front-engine design|Front engine]], [[rear-wheel drive]]/[[All wheel drive]]\n| predecessor = [[Mercedes-Benz W124]] (pre-facelift models, 1984\u20131993)\n}}\n\nThe '''Mercedes-Benz E-Class''' is a range of [[executive car]]s manufactured by German automaker [[Mercedes-Benz]] in various engine and body configurations. Produced since 1953, the E-Class falls midrange in the Mercedes line-up, and has been marketed worldwide across five generations.\n\nBefore 1993, the E in Mercedes-Benz nomenclature was a suffix following a vehicle's model number which stood for ''Einspritzmotor'' (German for [[fuel injection engine]]). It began to appear in the early 1960s, when that feature began to be utilized broadly in the maker's product line, and not just in its upper tier luxury and sporting models.  By the launch of the facelifted [[Mercedes-Benz W124|W124]] in 1993 fuel-injection was ubiquitous in Mercedes engines, and the E was adopted as a prefix (i.e., E 220) and the model line referred to officially as the E-Class (or ''E-Klasse''). All generations of the E-Class have offered either [[rear-wheel drive]] or Mercedes' [[4Matic]] [[four-wheel drive]] system. \n\nHistorically, the E-Class is Mercedes-Benz' best-selling model, with more than 13 million sold by 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mercedes-benz.com/en/mercedes-benz/classic/history/frist-new-e-class-rolls-off-the-production-line-in-sindelfingen/|title=First new E-Class rolls off the production line in Sindelfingen.|date=4 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref> The first E-Class series was originally available as four-door [[sedan (car)|sedan]], five-door [[station wagon]], 2 door coupe and 2 door convertible. From 1997 to 2009, the equivalent coupe and convertible were sold under the [[Mercedes-Benz CLK-Class]] nameplate; which was actually based on the mechanical underpinnings of the smaller C-Class while borrowing the styling and some powertrains from the E-Class, a trend continued with the C207 E-Class coupe/convertible which was sold parallel to the W212 E-Class sedan/wagon. With the latest incarnation of the E-Class released for the 2017 model year, all body styles share the same W213 platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/new-cars/first-drives/a32939/2018-mercedes-e400-coupe-first-drive/|title=The 2018 Mercedes E400 Coupe Is a Modern Take On an Old Formula|date=15 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nDue to the E-Class's size and durability, it has filled many market segments, from personal cars to frequently serving as [[Mercedes-Benz taxicab|taxis]] in European countries, as well special-purpose vehicles (e.g., police or ambulance modifications) from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mercedes-benz.de/content/germany/mpc/mpc_germany_website/de/home_mpc/sonderfahrzeuge0/home/products/branch-solutions/taxi0/e-klasse.html |title=Mercedes-Benz Deutschland \u2013 Sonderfahrzeuge \u2013 Taxi \u2013 E-Klasse |accessdate=2008-08-05 |publisher=[[Daimler AG]] |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917033105/http://www.mercedes-benz.de/content/germany/mpc/mpc_germany_website/de/home_mpc/sonderfahrzeuge0/home/products/branch-solutions/taxi0/e-klasse.html |archive-date=2008-09-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Predecessors ==\n[[File:Mercedes 190D (W121).jpg|thumb|160px|Mercedes 190D (W121)]]\n[[File:W110.jpg|thumb|160px|Mercedes Benz (W110)]]\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz 220D, circa 1974, Schaffen Diest, Fly-Drive 2013.JPG|thumb|160px|Mercedes-Benz (W115)]]\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz W123 front 20080822.jpg|thumb|160px|Mercedes-Benz (W123)]]\n=== W120 (1953\u20131962) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz W120}}\n\nThe first modern midsize Mercedes was the [[Mercedes-Benz W120|W120 'Ponton' 180]] of 1953 and was produced  until 1962. Sharing its engineering with the [[Mercedes-Benz R121|R121]] 190 SL of 1955, the Ponton was a stylish sedan with a [[Inline-four engine|four-cylinder engine]]. A larger-engined [[Mercedes-Benz W121|W121 190]] appeared in 1958.\n\n=== W110 (1961\u20131968) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz W110}}\n\nMercedes added tailfins to both the big [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class|S-Class]] and the new [[Mercedes-Benz W110|W110 'Fintail' 190]] of 1962. In the 1965 230 model a [[Straight-6]] engine appeared for the first time, and the four cylinder engine grew in displacement.\n\n=== W114, W115 (1968\u20131976) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz W114}}\n\nThe midsize Mercedes was redesigned in 1968 as the [[Mercedes-Benz W114|W114/W115 'Stroke-8']]. This time, the 6-cylinder models (The W114s) were most prevalent, with the W115 line making up the bottom of the company's offerings with four \u2013 and [[Straight-5|five-cylinder]] power. [[Diesel engine|Diesel]] engines joined the line-up, as did a [[coup\u00e9]] body.\n\n=== W123 (1976\u20131986) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz W123}}\n\nThe popular [[Mercedes-Benz W123|W123]] quickly became a best-seller on its launch in 1976. Especially in [[Diesel engine|diesel powered]] 200D and 240D (also the five-cylinder 300D) guises, the cars enhanced the company's reputation for product quality. Over 2.6 million were produced until the end of production in 1986.\nSaloon/Sedan, Coup\u00e9 and Estate body configurations were offered.\n\nThe engine is an M103 3.2 liter DOHC 4-valve 6-cylinder in-line cylinder with 220 horsepower.It is not a prominent specification at the moment, but at the time it was a 3 liter class engine with a good color appearance and a high performance as a smooth & powerful engine. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://antiquecars.info/mercedes-benz-e-class-320/ |title=Mercedes Benz E Class 320 |publisher=antiquecars.info |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== W124 (1986\u20131994) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz W124}}\n\nThe [[Mercedes-Benz W124|W124]] was presented in 1984 and introduced several new standards for a mid-size Mercedes.  It was the third car to inherit the company's new design theme since the late 1970s, following the flagship [[Mercedes-Benz W126|W126]] and compact [[Mercedes-Benz W201|W201]]. \n\nSimilar to its predecessors, the W124 also offered a coup\u00e9 and estate body styles. A new convertible (internally A124) was also available, making it the first mid-size Mercedes convertible.\n\n== E-Class ==\n\n=== First generation (W124; 1993\u20131995) ===\n\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz W124}}\n[[File:94-95 Mercedes-Benz E-Class sedan.jpg|thumb|right|Mercedes-Benz W124 (sedan)]]\nThe \"E-Class\" name first appeared in with the facelifted [[Mercedes-Benz W124|W124]] in 1993 for the model year 1994 (the W124 was introduced in 1984 but continued with the older naming convention until 1993, when all Mercedes-Benz models switched to a new system, e.g. E 320 instead of 300 E). The diesel versions continued to be the fuel economy option over the four and six-cylinder gasoline engines, and the gasoline [[V8 engine]]s (available after 1992) increased gasoline power outputs further. Four-cylinder gasoline models were not marketed in the United States. The V8 powered sedans/saloons were named 400 E/500 E from 1992\u20131993, and E 420/E 500 after 1993. Likewise, the 3.0-litre cars (e.g. 300 E) were also re-badged to E 320 with the new 3.2-litre ''M104'' engines and naming rationalization of 1994. For the diesel models the name change was less elegant, with the 250 D becoming the E 250 Diesel for example.\n\nSedan (W124), Coup\u00e9 (C124), Convertible (A124) and Estate (S124) body configurations were offered.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Second generation (W210; 1996\u20132002) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W210)}}\n[[File:1998 Mercedes-Benz E200 Elegance Automatic 2.0.jpg|thumb|right|Mercedes-Benz E 200 Elegance (United Kingdom; W210)]]\nThe [[Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W210)|W210]] E-Class, launched in 1995, brought the line firmly into the upper end of the mid-size luxury market. In September 1999 the W210 E-class was facelifted. This included visual, mechanical and quality improvements over the earlier versions.\n\nThe Mercedes-Benz E-Class was ''[[Motor Trend]]'''s [[Import Car of the Year]] for 1996.\n\nWhile the W210 sedan was replaced by the W211 in 2002, the wagon version continued to be sold until March 2003 when the W211 wagon replaced the W210 wagon.\n\n=== Third generation (W211; 2003\u20132009) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W211)}}\n[[File:Mercedes E 220 CDI Classic (W211) front 20100509.jpg|thumb|right|Mercedes-Benz E 220 CDI Classic (Europe)]]\nLaunched in 2002, the [[Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W211)|W211]] E-Class was another evolution of the previous model.  \n\nThe W211-based [[Mercedes-Benz CLS-Class (W219)|W219 CLS-Class]] sedan was introduced as a niche model in 2005, primarily to attract a younger demographic.\n\nThe W211 E-Class was facelifted in June 2006 for the 2007 [[model year]] to address quality and technical issues raised by earlier models, [[Sensotronic]] was dropped, while [[precrash system|Pre-Safe]] (w/o brake support) was made standard. The largest factory built engine in the E-class range is the E500 (badged E550 in the U.S.) which had its engine size increased from 5 litres to 5.5 litres in 2006 along with the facelift. There is also an AMG model badged E63 [[Mercedes-AMG|AMG]] and other tuning house installations.\n\nIn 2007 the diesel version of the E-Class was rebadged from CDI (Common rail Direct Injection) to Bluetec. While in some of the other Mercedes-Benz diesels urea injection was added, in the W211 E-Class the Bluetec name was only adopted to prevent confusion in the diesel lineup.\n\n=== Fourth generation (2010-2016) ===\n\n==== Sedan and wagon (W212) ====\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W212)}}\n[[File:2009 Mercedes-Benz E 250 CGI (W 212) Avantgarde sedan (2010-07-05).jpg|thumb|right|Mercedes-Benz E 250 CGI Avantgarde (Australia; W212)]]\nThe [[Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W212)|W212]] replaced the W211 in 2009 (as a 2010 model). Official photos of the W212 were leaked on the internet on 9 December 2008 ahead of its 2009 [[Geneva Motor Show]] unveiling.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoscoops.eu/nieuws/2008/mercedes-e-klasse-de-eerste-fotos |title=Mercedes E-Klasse: de eerste foto's |publisher=Autoscoops.eu |accessdate=2011-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120718133502/http://www.autoscoops.eu/nieuws/2008/mercedes-e-klasse-de-eerste-fotos |archivedate=2012-07-18 }}</ref> Scans of a leaked brochure were posted onto the internet in January 2009, detailing the whole E-Class range including the new E 200 CGI and E 230 CGI with [[gasoline direct injection|direct injected]] forced inducted engines.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tan |first=Paul |url=http://paultan.org/archives/2009/01/08/leaked-2010-mercedes-benz-e-class-w212-brochures-with-detailed-specification-sheets/ |title=Leaked 2010 Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W 212) Brochures with detailed specification sheets |publisher=Paultan.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-03}}</ref> New features included a [[blind spot monitor]], [[lane departure warning system|Lane Keeping Assist]], [[Precrash system|Pre-safe with Attention Assist]] and [[Night View Assist|Night View Assist Plus]]. In the United States the E-Class was priced nearly US$4,600 less than the previous model.<ref>{{cite web |last=Joseph |first=Noah |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/05/04/mercedes-slashes-nearly-5k-off-the-list-price-of-a-new-e-class/ |title=Mercedes slashes nearly $5k off the list price of a new E-Class \u2013 Autoblog |publisher=Autoblog.com |date=2009-04-05 |accessdate=2010-03-21}}</ref> The W212 estate was also announced and available from November 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carthusiast.com/2010-mercedes-e-class-estate-intelligent-estate-of-the-art-1877.html |title=2010 Mercedes E-Class Estate, Intelligent (E)state-of-the-art |publisher=Carthusiast.com |date=2009-08-06 |accessdate=2010-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122537/http://www.carthusiast.com/2010-mercedes-e-class-estate-intelligent-estate-of-the-art-1877.html |archive-date=2011-07-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nIn 2013, the E-Class was comprehensively [[Facelift (automotive)|facelifted]], featuring significant styling changes, fuel economy improvements and updated safety features. Daimler invested close to \u20ac1 billion into the development of the extensive refresh, making it likely the most expensive mid-life facelift in the history of the automobile.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoevolution.com/news/2014-w212-and-2017-w213-mercedes-e-class-sedans-spied-together-video-88669.html |title=2014 W212 and 2017 W213 Mercedes E-Class Sedans Spied Together [Video] |author=Mihnea Radu |work=autoevolution}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoevolution.com/news/mercedes-benz-e-350-w212-facelift-gets-reviewed-by-edmund-s-68614.html |title=Mercedes-Benz E 350 W212 Facelift Gets Reviewed by Edmund's |author=Alex Oagana |work=autoevolution}}</ref> The biggest change was the singular front lights replacing the twin headlamp design (marking the end of Mercedes's dual headlamps use) with integrated LED [[Daytime running lamps|DRLs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thechauffeur.com/new-mercedes-e-class-promises-to-give-rivals-a-rough-ride/ |title=New Mercedes E-Class promises to give rivals a rough ride |publisher=}}</ref> Although not an all-new model, the W212 facelift was the only mid-cycle refresh featured on a family portrait of several generations of the E-Class side by side by Mercedes-Benz for the unveiling of the W213 E-Class.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carscoops.com/2015/12/2017-mercedes-benz-e-class-exterior.html |title=2017 Mercedes-Benz E-Class Exterior Inadvertently Shown in Official Pics |author=Cristian Gnaticov |date=11 December 2015 |work=Carscoops}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caradvice.com.au/403102/2016-mercedes-benz-e-class-styling-revealed-in-interior-promo-shots/ |title=2016 Mercedes-Benz E-Class styling revealed in interior promo shots |work=CarAdvice.com.au}}</ref> While the factory has rated the E63S model at 577 hp/590 tq, there is significant real-world dynamometer testing that indicates the AMG-tuned S model exceeds 600 hp at the flywheel.\n\n==== Coupe and convertible (C207/A207) ====\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz E-Class (C207)}}\n[[File:2010 Mercedes-Benz E 350 (C 207) Avantgarde coupe (2010-12-28).jpg|thumb|right|Mercedes-Benz E 350 Avantgarde (Australia; C207)]]\nThe coup\u00e9 (C207) was first shown at the 2009 [[Geneva Motor Show]], while the convertible (A207) was unveiled at the 2010 [[North American International Auto Show]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorauthority.com/news/1032208_geneva-motor-show-debut-for-mercedes-benz-e-class-coupe|title=Geneva Motor Show debut for Mercedes Benz E-Class Coupe|work=Motor Authority|access-date=2018-05-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motor1.com/news/19514/2010-mercedes-benz-e-class-cabriolet-world-debut-in-detroit/|title=2010 Mercedes-Benz E-Class Cabriolet World Debut in Detroit|work=Motor1.com|access-date=2018-05-05|language=en}}</ref> Both models replaced the previous [[Mercedes-Benz CLK-Class (C209)|C209/A209 CLK-Class]] models. The C207/A207 E-Class is based on the [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W204)|W204 C-Class]] platform, and are produced alongside each other in the [[Bremen]] plant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autoblog.com/2009/05/19/2010-mercedes-benz-e-class-coupe-a-c-class-underneath/|title=2010 Mercedes-Benz E-Class Coupe a C-Class underneath?|work=Autoblog|access-date=2018-05-05|language=en}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Fifth generation (W213; 2017\u2013present) ===\n{{main article|Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W213)}}\n[[File: Mercedes-Benz_W213.jpg|thumb|right|Mercedes-Benz E 200 (W 213)]]\nThe fifth generation E-Class was unveiled at the 2016 [[North American International Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/115051193606/next-generation-mercedes-benz-e-class-sedan-will-likely |title=Next generation Mercedes-Benz E-Class Sedan will likely debut in January 2016 at NAIAS [spy video] |work=Motor1.com}}</ref> The next generation E-Class has design cues from the larger [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W222)|W222 S-Class]] and the smaller [[Mercedes-Benz C-Class (W205)|W205 C-Class]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autoevolution.com/news/2016-mercedes-e-class-w213-first-interior-spy-photos-s-class-inspiration-89573.html# |title=2016 Mercedes E-Class (W213) First Interior Spy Photos: S-CLass Inspiration |author=Mihnea Radu |work=autoevolution}}</ref> While the W212 E-Class has tighter surface and harder edges, the new model is curvier and more flowing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indianautosblog.com/2015/05/2016-mercedes-e-class-naias-2016-178443#ixzz3ZsnOcVNY |title=2016 Mercedes E Class to world debut at NAIAS 2016 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nEngine options for the W213 E-Class will see a major update, thanks to the switch to inline-6 engines from the current V6 engines,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carmagazine.co.uk/spy-shots/mercedes-benz/mercedes-e-class-2016-spied-straight-sixes-are-back/ |title=Mercedes E-class (2016) spied: straight sixes are back! |work=CAR Magazine}}</ref> along with a new generation of four-cylinder diesel engines, codenamed [[Mercedes-Benz OM654 engine|OM654]], and existing four-cylinder petrol engines.<ref name=\"2016eclassautocar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/2016-mercedes-benz-e-class-spotted-engines-and-launch-date |title=2016 Mercedes-Benz E-Class - engines and launch date |author=Greg Kable |work=autocar.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe W213 E-Class is the second most technologically advanced Mercedes after the new [[Mercedes-Benz S-Class|S Class]]. The E-Class received the latest in autonomous driving technology for use at highway speeds, capable of piloting itself up to speeds of {{convert|130|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} for up to 2 minutes. The system uses a complex array of motion sensors, radars and cameras to scan the road ahead, and requires the driver's hands to be placed on the wheel at all times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://performancedrive.com.au/2016-mercedes-e-class-will-be-capable-of-autonomous-driving-1020/ |title=2016 Mercedes E-Class will be capable of autonomous driving |work=PerformanceDrive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/115042292626/mercedes-benz-says-autonomous-technology-is-imminent |title=Mercedes-Benz says autonomous technology is imminent, could debut on 2016 E-Class |work=Worldcarfans}}</ref> This feature was also available on the 4th generation E63S AMG-tuned model.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Production and sales ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Calendar year\n!Production (sedan/estate/coupe/convertible) !!US sales !!Europe sales !!China sales<ref group=note>2011-2014 China sales only include locally produced versions, exclude imported versions</ref>\n|-\n| 2001\n| ||44,445<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Mercedes-Benz+USA+Records+Highest+Sales+in+Its+History.-a096075297 |title=Mercedes-Benz USA Records Highest Sales in Its History. \u2013 Free Online Library |publisher=Thefreelibrary.com |date=2003-01-03 |accessdate=2011-12-03}}</ref>|| 128,208||\n|-\n| 2002\n| ||42,598|| 156,317||\n|-\n| 2003\n| ||55,683<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/2005/01/04/313903.html |title=2004 Highest Year on Record for Mercedes-Benz USA |publisher=Theautochannel.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-21}}</ref>|| 191,809||\n|-\n| 2004\n| ||58,954|| 171,071||\n|-\n| 2005\n| ||50,383<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theautochann